# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atlantic-ocean
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atlantic-ocean/20th-meridian-east] The **meridian 20° east of Greenwich** is a line of longitude that extends from the North Pole across the Arctic Ocean, Europe, Africa, the Atlantic and Indian oceans, the Southern Ocean, and Antarctica to the South Pole.
[src:atlantic-ocean/20th-meridian-east] The 20th meridian east forms a great ellipse with the 160th meridian west.
[src:atlantic-ocean/20th-meridian-east] Part of Namibia's borders with Botswana and South Africa are defined by the meridian.
[src:atlantic-ocean/20th-meridian-east] The boundary between the Atlantic Ocean and the Indian Ocean is defined by the meridian.
[src:atlantic-ocean/20th-meridian-east] The meridian defines the eastern limit of the New Swabia area in Queen Maud Land, Antarctica.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] The **60th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 60 degrees north of Earth's equator.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] It crosses Europe, Asia, the Pacific Ocean, North America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] Although it lies approximately twice as far away from the Equator as from the North Pole, the 60th parallel is half as long as the Equator line, due to the cosine of 60 degrees being 0.5.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] This is where the Earth bulges halfway as much as on the Equator.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 7 minutes during the June solstice and 5 hours, 52 minutes during the December solstice.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is 53.44° on 21 June and 6.56° on 21 December.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 15.00º in October and > 8.00º in November.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] The lowest latitude where white nights can be observed is approximately on this parallel.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] White nights in the 60th parallel north occur around the June Solstice (Summer Solstice in the Northern Hemisphere).
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] During the summer solstice, nighttime does not get beyond nautical twilight, a condition which lasts throughout the month of June.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day between August 22 and April 21.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] Malachy Tallack wrote a book, *Sixty Degrees North: Around the World in Search of Home*, about his travels along the general line of the parallel, starting and finishing at Shetland.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] In Canada, the 60th parallel forms the southern mainland boundary of the northern territories of Yukon, Northwest Territories, and Nunavut with the western provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] Accordingly, "north of 60" is an expression often used for the territories, although parts of Nunavut (the islands in Hudson Bay and James Bay) are located south of the 60th parallel, and parts of Quebec and Newfoundland and Labrador are located north, to the east of Hudson Bay.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] A 1990s TV show on CBC about life in the Northwest Territories was called *North of 60*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] The 60th Parallel Territorial Park is on Mackenzie Highway between Alberta and Northwest Territories and it has a visitor centre there in the homeland of the Yellowknives Dene First Nation and the North Slave Métis Alliance.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] Canada's only four corners are located at the intersection of the 60th parallel and the 102nd meridian west, between the Northwest Territories, Nunavut, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-north] Between 1776 and 1950, the 60th parallel formed the southern limit of the Royal Greenland Trade Department's exclusive monopoly on trade near the Dano-Norwegian and later Danish colonies of Greenland (1776–1782) and South Greenland (1782–1950).
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] The **60th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 60 degrees south of Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] No land lies on the parallel—it crosses nothing but ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] The parallel marks the northern limit of the Southern Ocean (though some organisations and countries, notably Australia, have other definitions) and of the Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] It also marks the southern boundary of the South Pacific Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone and the Latin American Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 18 hours, 52 minutes during the December solstice and 5 hours, 52 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] On December 21, the sun is at 53.44 degrees up in the sky and 6.56 degrees on June 21.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] The sun's altitude is exactly 30 degrees at either equinox.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] The latitudes south of this parallel are often referred to as the Screaming 60s due to the prevailing high-speed, westerly winds which can generate large waves in excess of 15 m (50 ft) and peak wind speeds over 145 km/h (90 mph).
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 15.00º in April and > 8.00º in May.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] White nights in the 60th parallel south occur around the December Solstice (Summer Solstice in the Southern Hemisphere).
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] During the summer solstice, nighttime does not get beyond nautical twilight, a condition which lasts throughout the month of December.
[src:atlantic-ocean/60th-parallel-south] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day between February 17 and October 24.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The number of absolute monarchies in the world varies but some datasets agree that Brunei, Eswatini, Oman, Qatar, and Saudi Arabia are absolute monarchies, while others include Bahrain, Bhutan, Jordan, Kuwait, Liechtenstein, Monaco, Morocco, Tonga, Vatican City and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Absolute monarchies are distinct from hereditary dictatorships such as North Korea, Duvalier Haiti or Ba'athist Syria.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In the Ottoman Empire, the Sultan wielded absolute power over the state and was considered a Padishah, meaning "Great King" by his people.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Many sultans wielded absolute power through heavenly mandates reflected in their titles, such as "Shadow of God on Earth".
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In ancient Mesopotamia, many rulers of Assyria, Babylonia and Sumer were absolute monarchs as well.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Throughout Imperial China, many emperors and one empress (Wu Zetian) wielded absolute power through the Mandate of Heaven.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In pre-Columbian America, the Inca Empire was ruled by a Sapa Inca, who was considered the son of Inti, the sun god and absolute ruler over the people and nation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Korea under the Joseon dynasty and short-lived empire was also an absolute monarchy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Throughout much of European history, the divine right of kings was the theological justification for absolute monarchy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Many European monarchs claimed supreme autocratic power by divine right, and that their subjects had no rights to limit their power.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] James VI and I and his son Charles I tried to import the principle of divine right into Scotland and England.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] This law consequently authorized the king to abolish all other centers of power.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Most important was the abolition of the Council of the Realm in Denmark.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Absolute monarchy lasted until 1814 in Norway, and 1848 in Denmark.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The House of Habsburg is currently extinct in its male line, due to the death of the childless Charles II of Spain in 1700.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] However, the House of Habsburg-Lorraine still carries the female line of the House of Habsburg.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The first member of the House of Habsburg-Lorraine to rule over the Holy Roman Empire was Joseph II, a sovereign raised during the Enlightenment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Joseph II extended full legal freedom to serfs in 1781.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Franz Joseph I of Austria was Emperor of Austria from 1848 until his death in 1916 and was succeeded by Charles I of Austria.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Charles I was the last Emperor of Austria and abdicated on 12 November 1918 due to Austria-Hungary losing World War I.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Louis XIV (1638–1715) is said to have proclaimed *L'état, c'est moi!*, 'I am the State!'.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Although often criticized for his extravagances, such as the Palace of Versailles, he reigned over France for a long period.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The king of France concentrated legislative, executive, and judicial powers in his person.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] He could condemn people to death without the right of appeal.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] It was both his duty to punish offenses and stop them from being committed.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] From his judicial authority followed his power both to make laws and to annul them.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In Brandenburg-Prussia, the concept of absolute monarch took a notable turn from the above with its emphasis on the monarch as the "first servant of the state", but it also echoed many of the important characteristics of absolutism.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Prussia was ruled by the House of Hohenzollern as a feudal monarchy from 1525 to 1701 and an absolute monarchy from 1701 to 1848, after which it became a federal semi-constitutional monarchy from 1848 to 1918 until the monarchy was abolished during the German Revolution.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Frederick I was the first *King in Prussia*, beginning his reign on 18 January 1701.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] King Frederick the Great adopted the title *King of Prussia* in 1772, the same year he annexed most of Royal Prussia in the First Partition of Poland, and practiced enlightened absolutism until his death in 1786.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] He introduced a general civil code, abolished torture and established the principle that the Crown would not interfere in matters of justice.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] He also promoted an advanced secondary education, the forerunner of today's German gymnasium (grammar school) system, which prepares high achieving students for university studies.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The Prussian education system was emulated in various countries, including the United States.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Until 1905, the tsars and emperors of Russia governed as absolute monarchs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Ivan IV ("the Terrible") was known for his reign of terror through the *oprichnina*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Following the Time of Troubles in the early 17th century, the traditional alliance of autocratic monarchy, the church, and the aristocracy was widely seen as the only basis for preserving the social order and Russian statehood, which legitimized the rule of the Romanov dynasty.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Peter I ("the Great") reduced the power of the Russian nobility and strengthened the central power of the monarch, establishing a bureaucracy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] This tradition of absolutism was expanded by Catherine II and her descendants.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Russia became the last European country (excluding Vatican City) to abolish absolutism, and it was the only one to do so as late as the 20th century (the Ottoman Empire drafted its first constitution in 1876).
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Russia was one of the four continental empires which collapsed after World War I, along with Germany, Austria–Hungary, and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In 1918, the Bolsheviks executed the Romanov family, ending three centuries of Romanov rule.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The Revolutions of 1848, known in some countries as the *Springtime of the Peoples* or the *Springtime of Nations*, were a series of political upheavals throughout Europe in 1848.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Many nations formerly with absolute monarchies, such as Jordan, Kuwait, Morocco and Qatar, have *de jure* moved towards a constitutional monarchy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] However, in these cases, the monarch still retains tremendous powers, even to the extent that by some measures, parliament's influence on political life is viewed as negligible or merely consultative.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In Nepal, there were several swings between constitutional rule and direct rule related to the Nepalese Civil War, the Maoist insurgency, and the 2001 Nepalese royal massacre, with the Nepalese monarchy being abolished on 28 May 2008.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In Tonga, the king had majority control of the Legislative Assembly until 2010.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Liechtenstein has moved towards expanding the power of the monarch—the Prince of Liechtenstein was given vast expanded powers after a referendum to amend the Constitution of Liechtenstein in 2003, which led BBC News to describe the prince as an "absolute monarch again".
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The referendum granted the monarch the powers to dismiss the government, nominate judges and veto legislation, among others.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Just prior to the referendum, the Venice Commission of the Council of Europe published a comprehensive report analysing the amendments, opining that they were not compatible with the European standards of democracy, effectively making Liechtenstein a *de facto* absolute monarchy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Prince Hans-Adam II had also previously threatened to leave the country and move his assets out of Liechtenstein if voters had chosen to restrict his powers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Vatican City continues to be an absolute monarchy, but is unique because it is also a microstate, ecclesiastical jurisdiction, and elective monarchy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] As of 2023, Vatican City has a population of 764 residents (regardless of citizenship).
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] It is the smallest state in the world both by area and by population.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The Pope is the absolute monarch of Vatican City, and is elected by a papal conclave with a two-thirds supermajority.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] As governed by the Holy See, Vatican City State is an sacerdotal-monarchical state ruled by the Pope, who is the bishop of Rome and head of the Catholic Church.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Unlike citizenship of other states, which is based either on *jus sanguinis* or *jus soli*, citizenship of Vatican City is granted on *jus officii*, namely on the grounds of appointment to work in a certain capacity in the service of the Holy See.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] It usually ceases upon cessation of the appointment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Citizenship is also extended to the spouse and children of a citizen, provided they are living together in the city.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Saudi Arabia is an absolute monarchy, and according to the Basic Law of Saudi Arabia adopted by Royal Decree in 1992, the King must comply with Sharia (Islamic law) and the Quran.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] No political parties or national elections are permitted.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The Saudi government is the world's most authoritarian regime in 2023 measured by the electoral democracy score of the V-Dem Democracy indices.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Oman is an absolute monarchy, with the sultan of Oman being both head of state and head of government.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The sultan is hereditary, who appoints a cabinet to assist him.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] The sultan also serves as the supreme commander of the armed forces and prime minister.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] There is a considerable variety of opinion by historians on the extent of absolutism among European monarchs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Some, such as Perry Anderson, argue that quite a few monarchs achieved levels of absolutist control over their states, while historians such as Roger Mettam dispute the very concept of absolutism.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] In the 17th century, French legal theorist Jean Domat defended the concept of absolute monarchy in works such as *"On Social Order and Absolute Monarchy"*, citing absolute monarchy as preserving natural order as God intended.
[src:atlantic-ocean/absolute-monarchy] Other intellectual figures who supported absolute monarchy include Thomas Hobbes and Charles Maurras.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] An **abyssal plain** is an underwater plain on the deep ocean floor, usually found at depths between 3,000 and 6,000 metres (9,800 and 19,700 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Lying generally between the foot of a continental rise and a mid-ocean ridge, abyssal plains cover more than 50% of the Earth's surface.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] They are among the flattest, smoothest, and least explored regions on Earth.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal plains are key geologic elements of oceanic basins, the other elements being an elevated mid-ocean ridge and flanking abyssal hills.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The creation of the abyssal plain is the result of the spreading of the seafloor (plate tectonics) and the melting of the lower oceanic crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Magma rises from above the asthenosphere (a layer of the upper mantle), and as this basaltic material reaches the surface at mid-ocean ridges, it forms new oceanic crust, which is constantly pulled sideways by spreading of the seafloor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal plains result from the blanketing of an originally uneven surface of oceanic crust by fine-grained sediments, mainly clay and silt.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Much of this sediment is deposited by turbidity currents that have been channelled from the continental margins along submarine canyons into deeper water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The rest is composed chiefly of pelagic sediments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Metallic nodules are common in some areas of the plains, with varying concentrations of metals, including manganese, iron, nickel, cobalt, and copper.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] There are also amounts of carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus and silicon, due to material that comes down and decomposes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Owing in part to their vast size, abyssal plains are believed to be major reservoirs of biodiversity.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] They also exert significant influence upon ocean carbon cycling, dissolution of calcium carbonate, and atmospheric CO2 concentrations over time scales of a hundred to a thousand years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The structure of abyssal ecosystems is strongly influenced by the rate of flux of food to the seafloor and the composition of the material that settles.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Factors such as climate change, fishing practices, and ocean fertilization have a substantial effect on patterns of primary production in the euphotic zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Animals absorb dissolved oxygen from the oxygen-poor waters.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Much dissolved oxygen in abyssal plains came from polar regions that had melted long ago.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Due to scarcity of oxygen, abyssal plains are inhospitable for organisms that would flourish in the oxygen-enriched waters above.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Deep sea coral reefs are mainly found in depths of 3,000 meters and deeper in the abyssal and hadal zones.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal plains were not recognized as distinct physiographic features of the sea floor until the late 1940s and, until recently, none had been studied on a systematic basis.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] They are poorly preserved in the sedimentary record, because they tend to be consumed by the subduction process.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Due to darkness and a water pressure that can reach about 750 times atmospheric pressure (76 megapascal), abyssal plains are not well explored.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The ocean can be conceptualized as zones, depending on depth, and presence or absence of sunlight.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Nearly all life forms in the ocean depend on the photosynthetic activities of phytoplankton and other marine plants to convert carbon dioxide into organic carbon, which is the basic building block of organic matter.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Photosynthesis in turn requires energy from sunlight to drive the chemical reactions that produce organic carbon.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The stratum of the water column nearest the surface of the ocean (sea level) is referred to as the photic zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The photic zone can be subdivided into two different vertical regions.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The uppermost portion of the photic zone, where there is adequate light to support photosynthesis by phytoplankton and plants, is referred to as the euphotic zone (also referred to as the *epipelagic zone*, or *surface zone*).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The lower portion of the photic zone, where the light intensity is insufficient for photosynthesis, is called the dysphotic zone (dysphotic means "poorly lit" in Greek).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The dysphotic zone is also referred to as the *mesopelagic zone*, or the *twilight zone*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Its lowermost boundary is at a thermocline of 12 °C (54 °F), which, in the tropics generally lies between 200 and 1,000 metres (660 and 3,280 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The euphotic zone is somewhat arbitrarily defined as extending from the surface to the depth where the light intensity is approximately 0.1–1% of surface sunlight irradiance, depending on season, latitude and degree of water turbidity.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In the clearest ocean water, the euphotic zone may extend to a depth of about 150 m, or rarely, up to 200 m.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Dissolved substances and solid particles absorb and scatter light, and in coastal regions the high concentration of these substances causes light to be attenuated rapidly with depth.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In such areas the euphotic zone may be only a few tens of metres deep or less.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The dysphotic zone, where light intensity is considerably less than 1% of surface irradiance, extends from the base of the euphotic zone to about 1,000 m.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Extending from the bottom of the photic zone down to the seabed is the aphotic zone, a region of perpetual darkness.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Since the average depth of the ocean is about 4,300 m (14,100 ft), the photic zone represents only a tiny fraction of the ocean's total volume.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] However, due to its capacity for photosynthesis, the photic zone has the greatest biodiversity and biomass of all oceanic zones.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Nearly all primary production in the ocean occurs here.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Life forms which inhabit the aphotic zone are often capable of movement upwards through the water column into the photic zone for feeding.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Otherwise, they must rely on material sinking from above, or find another source of energy and nutrition, such as occurs in chemosynthetic archaea found near hydrothermal vents and cold seeps.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The aphotic zone can be subdivided into three different vertical regions, based on depth and temperature.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] First is the bathyal zone, extending from a depth of 1,000 to 3,000 m (3,300 to 9,800 ft), with water temperature decreasing from 12 °C (54 °F) to 4 °C (39 °F) as depth increases.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Next is the abyssal zone, extending from a depth of 3,000 to 6,000 m (9,800 to 19,700 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The final zone includes the deep oceanic trenches, and is known as the hadal zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This, the deepest oceanic zone, extends from a depth of 6,000 m to approximately 11,034 m (36,201 ft), at the very bottom of the Mariana Trench, the deepest point on Earth.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal plains are typically in the abyssal zone, at depths from 3,000 to 6,000 m.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Oceanic crust, which forms the bedrock of abyssal plains, is continuously being created at mid-ocean ridges (a type of divergent boundary) by a process known as decompression melting.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Plume-related decompression melting of solid mantle is responsible for creating ocean islands like the Hawaiian islands, as well as the ocean crust at mid-ocean ridges.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This phenomenon is also the most common explanation for flood basalts and oceanic plateaus (two types of large igneous provinces).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Decompression melting occurs when the upper mantle is partially melted into magma as it moves upwards under mid-ocean ridges.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This upwelling magma then cools and solidifies by conduction and convection of heat to form new oceanic crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Accretion occurs as mantle is added to the growing edges of a tectonic plate, usually associated with seafloor spreading.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The age of oceanic crust is therefore a function of distance from the mid-ocean ridge.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The youngest oceanic crust is at the mid-ocean ridges, and it becomes progressively older, cooler and denser as it migrates outwards from the mid-ocean ridges as part of the process called mantle convection.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The lithosphere, which rides atop the asthenosphere, is divided into a number of tectonic plates that are continuously being created and consumed at their opposite plate boundaries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Oceanic crust and tectonic plates are formed and move apart at mid-ocean ridges.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal hills are formed by stretching of the oceanic lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Consumption or destruction of the oceanic lithosphere occurs at oceanic trenches (a type of convergent boundary, also known as a destructive plate boundary) by a process known as subduction.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Oceanic trenches are found at places where the oceanic lithospheric slabs of two different plates meet, and the denser (older) slab begins to descend back into the mantle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] At the consumption edge of the plate (the oceanic trench), the oceanic lithosphere has thermally contracted to become quite dense, and it sinks under its own weight in the process of subduction.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The subduction process consumes older oceanic lithosphere, so oceanic crust is seldom more than 200 million years old.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The overall process of repeated cycles of creation and destruction of oceanic crust is known as the Supercontinent cycle, first proposed by Canadian geophysicist and geologist John Tuzo Wilson.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] New oceanic crust, closest to the mid-oceanic ridges, is mostly basalt at shallow levels and has a rugged topography.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The roughness of this topography is a function of the rate at which the mid-ocean ridge is spreading (the spreading rate).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Magnitudes of spreading rates vary quite significantly.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Typical values for fast-spreading ridges are greater than 100 mm/yr, while slow-spreading ridges are typically less than 20 mm/yr.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Studies have shown that the slower the spreading rate, the rougher the new oceanic crust will be, and vice versa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] It is thought this phenomenon is due to faulting at the mid-ocean ridge when the new oceanic crust was formed.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] These faults pervading the oceanic crust, along with their bounding abyssal hills, are the most common tectonic and topographic features on the surface of the Earth.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The process of seafloor spreading helps to explain the concept of continental drift in the theory of plate tectonics.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The flat appearance of mature abyssal plains results from the blanketing of this originally uneven surface of oceanic crust by fine-grained sediments, mainly clay and silt.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Much of this sediment is deposited from turbidity currents that have been channeled from the continental margins along submarine canyons down into deeper water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The remainder of the sediment comprises chiefly dust (clay particles) blown out to sea from land, and the remains of small marine plants and animals which sink from the upper layer of the ocean, known as pelagic sediments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The total sediment deposition rate in remote areas is estimated at two to three centimeters per thousand years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Sediment-covered abyssal plains are less common in the Pacific Ocean than in other major ocean basins because sediments from turbidity currents are trapped in oceanic trenches that border the Pacific.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal plains are typically covered by deep sea, but during parts of the Messinian salinity crisis much of the Mediterranean Sea's abyssal plain was exposed to air as an empty deep hot dry salt-floored sink.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The landmark scientific expedition (December 1872 – May 1876) of the British Royal Navy survey ship HMS *Challenger* yielded a tremendous amount of bathymetric data, much of which has been confirmed by subsequent researchers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Bathymetric data obtained during the course of the Challenger expedition enabled scientists to draw maps, which provided a rough outline of certain major submarine terrain features, such as the edge of the continental shelves and the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This discontinuous set of data points was obtained by the simple technique of taking soundings by lowering long lines from the ship to the seabed.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The Challenger expedition was followed by the 1879–1881 expedition of the *Jeannette*, led by United States Navy Lieutenant George Washington DeLong.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The team sailed across the Chukchi Sea and recorded meteorological and astronomical data in addition to taking soundings of the seabed.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The ship became trapped in the ice pack near Wrangel Island in September 1879, and was ultimately crushed and sunk in June 1881.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The *Jeannette* expedition was followed by the 1893–1896 Arctic expedition of Norwegian explorer Fridtjof Nansen aboard the *Fram*, which proved that the Arctic Ocean was a deep oceanic basin, uninterrupted by any significant land masses north of the Eurasian continent.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Beginning in 1916, Canadian physicist Robert William Boyle and other scientists of the Anti-Submarine Detection Investigation Committee (ASDIC) undertook research which ultimately led to the development of sonar technology.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Acoustic sounding equipment was developed which could be operated much more rapidly than the sounding lines, thus enabling the German Meteor expedition aboard the German research vessel Meteor (1925–27) to take frequent soundings on east-west Atlantic transects.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Maps produced from these techniques show the major Atlantic basins, but the depth precision of these early instruments was not sufficient to reveal the flat featureless abyssal plains.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] As technology improved, measurement of depth, latitude and longitude became more precise and it became possible to collect more or less continuous sets of data points.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This allowed researchers to draw accurate and detailed maps of large areas of the ocean floor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Use of a continuously recording fathometer enabled Tolstoy & Ewing in the summer of 1947 to identify and describe the first abyssal plain.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This plain, south of Newfoundland, is now known as the Sohm Abyssal Plain.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Following this discovery many other examples were found in all the oceans.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The Challenger Deep is the deepest surveyed point of all of Earth's oceans; it is at the south end of the Mariana Trench near the Mariana Islands group.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The depression is named after HMS *Challenger*, whose researchers made the first recordings of its depth on 23 March 1875 at station 225.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The reported depth was 4,475 fathoms (8184 m) based on two separate soundings.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] On 1 June 2009, sonar mapping of the Challenger Deep by the Simrad EM120 multibeam sonar bathymetry system aboard the R/V *Kilo Moana* indicated a maximum depth of 10,971 m (6.82 miles).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The sonar system uses phase and amplitude bottom detection, with an accuracy of better than 0.2% of water depth (an error of about 22 m at this depth).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] A rare but important terrain feature found in the bathyal, abyssal and hadal zones is the hydrothermal vent.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In contrast to the approximately 2 °C ambient water temperature at these depths, water emerges from these vents at temperatures ranging from 60 °C up to as high as 464 °C.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Due to the high hydrostatic pressure at these depths, water may exist in either its liquid form or as a supercritical fluid at such temperatures.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] At a hydrostatic pressure of 218 atmospheres, the critical point of water is 375 °C.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] At a depth of 3,000 m, the hydrostatic pressure of sea water is more than 300 atmospheres (as salt water is denser than fresh water).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] At this depth and pressure, seawater becomes supercritical at a temperature of 407 °C (*see image*).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] However the increase in salinity at this depth pushes the water closer to its critical point.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Thus, water emerging from the hottest parts of some hydrothermal vents, *black smokers* and submarine volcanoes can be a supercritical fluid, possessing physical properties between those of a gas and those of a liquid.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Hydrothermal vents in the deep ocean typically form along the mid-ocean ridges, such as the East Pacific Rise and the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] These are locations where two tectonic plates are diverging and new crust is being formed.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Another unusual feature found in the abyssal and hadal zones is the cold seep, sometimes called a *cold vent*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This is an area of the seabed where seepage of hydrogen sulfide, methane and other hydrocarbon-rich fluid occurs, often in the form of a deep-sea brine pool.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The first cold seeps were discovered in 1983, at a depth of 3,200 m in the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Though the plains were once assumed to be vast, desert-like habitats, research over the past decade or so shows that they teem with a wide variety of microbial life.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] However, ecosystem structure and function at the deep seafloor have historically been poorly studied because of the size and remoteness of the abyss.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] New species make up more than 80% of the thousands of seafloor invertebrate species collected at any abyssal station, highlighting our heretofore poor understanding of abyssal diversity and evolution.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Richer biodiversity is associated with areas of known phytodetritus input and higher organic carbon flux.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] CeDAMar scientists have demonstrated that some abyssal and hadal species have a cosmopolitan distribution.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] One example of this would be protozoan foraminiferans, certain species of which are distributed from the Arctic to the Antarctic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Other faunal groups, such as the polychaete worms and isopod crustaceans, appear to be endemic to certain specific plains and basins.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Many apparently unique taxa of nematode worms have also been recently discovered on abyssal plains.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This suggests that the deep ocean has fostered adaptive radiations.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The taxonomic composition of the nematode fauna in the abyssal Pacific is similar, but not identical to, that of the North Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] A list of some of the species that have been discovered or redescribed by CeDAMar can be found here.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Eleven of the 31 described species of *Monoplacophora* (a class of mollusks) live below 2,000 m.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Of these 11 species, two live exclusively in the hadal zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The greatest number of monoplacophorans are from the eastern Pacific Ocean along the oceanic trenches.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] However, no abyssal monoplacophorans have yet been found in the Western Pacific and only one abyssal species has been identified in the Indian Ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Of the 922 known species of chitons (from the *Polyplacophora* class of mollusks), 22 species (2.4%) are reported to live below 2,000 m and two of them are restricted to the abyssal plain.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Although genetic studies are lacking, at least six of these species are thought to be eurybathic (capable of living in a wide range of depths), having been reported as occurring from the sublittoral to abyssal depths.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] A large number of the polyplacophorans from great depths are herbivorous or xylophagous, which could explain the difference between the distribution of monoplacophorans and polyplacophorans in the world's oceans.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Peracarid crustaceans, including isopods, are known to form a significant part of the macrobenthic community that is responsible for scavenging on large food falls onto the sea floor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In 2003, De Broyer et al. collected some 68,000 peracarid crustaceans from 62 species from baited traps deployed in the Weddell Sea, Scotia Sea, and off the South Shetland Islands.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] They found that about 98% of the specimens belonged to the amphipod superfamily *Lysianassoidea*, and 2% to the isopod family Cirolanidae.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Half of these species were collected from depths of greater than 1000 meters.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In 2005, the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology (JAMSTEC) remotely operated vehicle, KAIKO, collected sediment core from the Challenger Deep.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] 432 living specimens of soft-walled foraminifera were identified in the sediment samples.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Foraminifera are single-celled protists that construct shells.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] There are an estimated 4,000 species of living foraminifera.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Out of the 432 organisms collected, the overwhelming majority of the sample consisted of simple, soft-shelled foraminifera, with others representing species of the complex, multi-chambered genera *Leptohalysis* and *Reophax*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Overall, 85% of the specimens consisted of soft-shelled allogromiids.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This is unusual compared to samples of sediment-dwelling organisms from other deep-sea environments, where the percentage of organic-walled foraminifera ranges from 5% to 20% of the total.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Small organisms with hard calciferous shells have trouble growing at extreme depths because the water at that depth is severely lacking in calcium carbonate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The giant (5–20 cm) foraminifera known as xenophyophores are only found at depths of 500–10,000 m (1,600–32,800 ft), where they can occur in great numbers and greatly increase animal diversity due to their bioturbation and provision of living habitat for small animals.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] While similar lifeforms have been known to exist in shallower oceanic trenches (>7,000 m) and on the abyssal plain, the lifeforms discovered in the Challenger Deep may represent independent taxa from those shallower ecosystems.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This preponderance of soft-shelled organisms at the Challenger Deep may be a result of selection pressure.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Millions of years ago, the Challenger Deep was shallower than it is now.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Over the past six to nine million years, as the Challenger Deep grew to its present depth, many of the species present in the sediment of that ancient biosphere were unable to adapt to the increasing water pressure and changing environment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Those species that were able to adapt may have been the ancestors of the organisms currently endemic to the Challenger Deep.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Polychaetes occur throughout the Earth's oceans at all depths, from forms that live as plankton near the surface, to the deepest oceanic trenches.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The robot ocean probe Nereus observed a 2–3 cm specimen (still unclassified) of polychaete at the bottom of the Challenger Deep on 31 May 2009.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] There are more than 10,000 described species of polychaetes; they can be found in nearly every marine environment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Some species live in the coldest ocean temperatures of the hadal zone, while others can be found in the extremely hot waters adjacent to hydrothermal vents.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Within the abyssal and hadal zones, the areas around submarine hydrothermal vents and cold seeps have by far the greatest biomass and biodiversity per unit area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In these locations, chemosynthetic archaea and bacteria typically form the base of the food chain.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Although the process of chemosynthesis is entirely microbial, these chemosynthetic microorganisms often support vast ecosystems consisting of complex multicellular organisms through symbiosis.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] These communities are characterized by species such as vesicomyid clams, mytilid mussels, limpets, isopods, giant tube worms, soft corals, eelpouts, galatheid crabs, and alvinocarid shrimp.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The deepest seep community discovered thus far is in the Japan Trench, at a depth of 7700 meters.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Probably the most important ecological characteristic of abyssal ecosystems is energy limitation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Abyssal seafloor communities are considered to be *food limited* because benthic production depends on the input of detrital organic material produced in the euphotic zone, thousands of meters above.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Most of the organic flux arrives as an attenuated rain of small particles (typically, only 0.5–2% of net primary production in the euphotic zone), which decreases inversely with water depth.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The small particle flux can be augmented by the fall of larger carcasses and downslope transport of organic material near continental margins.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In addition to their high biodiversity, abyssal plains are of great current and future commercial and strategic interest.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] For example, they may be used for the legal and illegal disposal of large structures such as ships and oil rigs, radioactive waste and other hazardous waste, such as munitions.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] They may also be attractive sites for deep-sea fishing, and extraction of oil and gas and other minerals.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Future deep-sea waste disposal activities that could be significant by 2025 include emplacement of sewage and sludge, carbon sequestration, and disposal of dredge spoils.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] As fish stocks dwindle in the upper ocean, deep-sea fisheries are increasingly being targeted for exploitation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Because deep sea fish are long-lived and slow growing, these deep-sea fisheries are not thought to be sustainable in the long term given current management practices.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Changes in primary production in the photic zone are expected to alter the standing stocks in the food-limited aphotic zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Hydrocarbon exploration in deep water occasionally results in significant environmental degradation resulting mainly from accumulation of contaminated drill cuttings, but also from oil spills.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] While the oil blowout involved in the Deepwater Horizon oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico originates from a wellhead only 1,500 m below the ocean surface, it nevertheless illustrates the kind of environmental disaster that can result from mishaps related to offshore drilling for oil and gas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Sediments of certain abyssal plains contain abundant mineral resources, notably polymetallic nodules.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] These potato-sized concretions of manganese, iron, nickel, cobalt, and copper, distributed on the seafloor at depths of greater than 4,000 m, are of significant commercial interest.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The area of maximum commercial interest for polymetallic nodule mining (called the Pacific nodule province) lies in international waters of the Pacific Ocean, stretching from 118°–157°, and from 9°–16°N, an area of more than 3 million km2.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] The abyssal Clarion-Clipperton fracture zone (CCFZ) is an area within the Pacific nodule province that is currently under exploration for its mineral potential.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] When mining ultimately begins, each mining operation is projected to directly disrupt 300–800 km2 of seafloor per year and disturb the benthic fauna over an area 5–10 times that size due to redeposition of suspended sediments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Thus, over the 15-year projected duration of a single mining operation, nodule mining might severely damage abyssal seafloor communities over areas of 20,000 to 45,000 km2 (a zone at least the size of Massachusetts).
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Limited knowledge of the taxonomy, biogeography and natural history of deep sea communities prevents accurate assessment of the risk of species extinctions from large-scale mining.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Data acquired from the abyssal North Pacific and North Atlantic suggest that deep-sea ecosystems may be adversely affected by mining operations on decadal time scales.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In 1978, a dredge aboard the Hughes Glomar Explorer, operated by the American mining consortium Ocean Minerals Company (OMCO), made a mining track at a depth of 5,000 m in the nodule fields of the CCFZ.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] In 2004, the French Research Institute for Exploitation of the Sea (IFREMER) conducted the *Nodinaut* expedition to this mining track (which is still visible on the seabed) to study the long-term effects of this physical disturbance on the sediment and its benthic fauna.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] Samples taken of the superficial sediment revealed that its physical and chemical properties had not shown any recovery since the disturbance made 26 years earlier.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] On the other hand, the biological activity measured in the track by instruments aboard the crewed submersible bathyscaphe *Nautile* did not differ from a nearby unperturbed site.
[src:atlantic-ocean/abyssal-plain] This data suggests that the benthic fauna and nutrient fluxes at the water–sediment interface has fully recovered.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] A **convergent boundary** (also known as a **destructive boundary**) is an area on Earth where two or more lithospheric plates collide.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] One plate eventually slides beneath the other, a process known as subduction.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The subduction zone can be defined by a plane where many earthquakes occur, called the Wadati–Benioff zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] These collisions happen on scales of millions to tens of millions of years and can lead to volcanism, earthquakes, orogenesis, destruction of lithosphere, and deformation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Convergent boundaries occur between oceanic-oceanic lithosphere, oceanic-continental lithosphere, and continental-continental lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The geologic features related to convergent boundaries vary depending on crust types.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Plate tectonics is driven by convection currents in the mantle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Convection cells are the result of heat generated by the radioactive decay of elements in the mantle escaping to the surface and the return of cool materials from the surface to the mantle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] These convection cells bring hot mantle material to the surface along spreading centers creating new crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] As this new crust is pushed away from the spreading center by the formation of newer crust, it cools, thins, and becomes denser.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Subduction begins when this dense crust converges with a less dense crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The force of gravity helps drive the subducting slab into the mantle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] As the relatively cool subducting slab sinks deeper into the mantle, it is heated, causing hydrous minerals to break down.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] This releases water into the hotter asthenosphere, which leads to partial melting of the asthenosphere and volcanism.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Both dehydration and partial melting occur along the 1,000 °C (1,830 °F) isotherm, generally at depths of 65 to 130 km (40 to 81 mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Some lithospheric plates consist of both continental and oceanic lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] In some instances, initial convergence with another plate will destroy oceanic lithosphere, leading to convergence of two continental plates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] It is likely that the plate may break along the boundary of continental and oceanic crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Seismic tomography reveals pieces of lithosphere that have broken off during convergence.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Subduction zones are areas where one lithospheric plate slides beneath another at a convergent boundary due to lithospheric differences.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] These plates dip at an average of 45° but can vary.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Subduction zones are often marked by an abundance of earthquakes, the result of internal deformation of the plate, convergence with the opposing plate, and bending at the oceanic trench.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Earthquakes have been detected to a depth of 670 km (416 mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The relatively cold and dense subducting plates are pulled into the mantle and help drive mantle convection.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] In collisions between two oceanic plates, the cooler, denser oceanic lithosphere sinks beneath the warmer, less dense oceanic lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] As the slab sinks deeper into the mantle, it releases water from dehydration of hydrous minerals in the oceanic crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] This water reduces the melting temperature of rocks in the asthenosphere and causes partial melting.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Partial melt will travel up through the asthenosphere, eventually, reach the surface, and form volcanic island arcs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] When oceanic lithosphere and continental lithosphere collide, the dense oceanic lithosphere subducts beneath the less dense continental lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] An accretionary wedge forms on the continental crust as deep-sea sediments and oceanic crust are scraped from the oceanic plate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Volcanic arcs form on continental lithosphere as the result of partial melting due to dehydration of the hydrous minerals of the subducting slab.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Some lithospheric plates consist of both continental and oceanic crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Subduction initiates as oceanic lithosphere slides beneath continental crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] As the oceanic lithosphere subducts to greater depths, the attached continental crust is pulled closer to the subduction zone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Once the continental lithosphere reaches the subduction zone, subduction processes are altered, since continental lithosphere is more buoyant and resists subduction beneath other continental lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] A small portion of the continental crust may be subducted until the slab breaks, allowing the oceanic lithosphere to continue subducting, hot asthenosphere to rise and fill the void, and the continental lithosphere to rebound.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Evidence of this continental rebound includes ultrahigh pressure metamorphic rocks, which form at depths of 90 to 125 km (56 to 78 mi), that are exposed at the surface.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Seismic records have been used to map the torn slabs beneath the Caucasus continental – continental convergence zone, and seismic tomography has mapped detached slabs beneath the Tethyan suture zone (the Alps – Zagros – Himalaya mountain belt).
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The oceanic crust contains hydrated minerals such as the amphibole and mica groups.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] During subduction, oceanic lithosphere is heated and metamorphosed, causing breakdown of these hydrous minerals, which releases water into the asthenosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The release of water into the asthenosphere leads to partial melting.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Partial melting allows the rise of more buoyant, hot material and can lead to volcanism at the surface and emplacement of plutons in the subsurface.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] These processes which generate magma are not entirely understood.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Where these magmas reach the surface they create volcanic arcs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Volcanic arcs can form as island arc chains or as arcs on continental crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Three magma series of volcanic rocks are found in association with arcs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The chemically reduced tholeiitic magma series is most characteristic of oceanic volcanic arcs, though this is also found in continental volcanic arcs above rapid subduction (>7 cm/year).
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] This series is relatively low in potassium.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The more oxidized calc-alkaline series, which is moderately enriched in potassium and incompatible elements, is characteristic of continental volcanic arcs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The alkaline magma series (highly enriched in potassium) is sometimes present in the deeper continental interior.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The shoshonite series, which is extremely high in potassium, is rare but sometimes is found in volcanic arcs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The andesite member of each series is typically most abundant, and the transition from basaltic volcanism of the deep Pacific basin to andesitic volcanism in the surrounding volcanic arcs has been called the andesite line.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Back-arc basins form behind a volcanic arc and are associated with extensional tectonics and high heat flow, often being home to seafloor spreading centers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] These spreading centers are like mid-ocean ridges, though the magma composition of back-arc basins is generally more varied and contains a higher water content than mid-ocean ridge magmas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Back-arc basins are often characterized by thin, hot lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Opening of back-arc basins may arise from movement of hot asthenosphere into lithosphere, causing extension.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Oceanic trenches are narrow topographic lows that mark convergent boundaries or subduction zones.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Oceanic trenches average 50 to 100 km (31 to 62 mi) wide and can be several thousand kilometers long.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Oceanic trenches form as a result of bending of the subducting slab.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Depth of oceanic trenches seems to be controlled by age of the oceanic lithosphere being subducted.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Sediment fill in oceanic trenches varies and generally depends on abundance of sediment input from surrounding areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] An oceanic trench, the Mariana Trench, is the deepest point of the ocean at a depth of approximately 11,000 m (36,089 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Earthquakes are common along convergent boundaries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] A region of high earthquake activity, the Wadati–Benioff zone, generally dips 45° and marks the subducting plate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Earthquakes will occur to a depth of 670 km (416 mi) along the Wadati-Benioff margin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Both compressional and extensional forces act along convergent boundaries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] On the inner walls of trenches, compressional faulting or reverse faulting occurs due to the relative motion of the two plates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Reverse faulting scrapes off ocean sediment and leads to the formation of an accretionary wedge.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Reverse faulting can lead to megathrust earthquakes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Tensional or normal faulting occurs on the outer wall of the trench, likely due to bending of the downgoing slab.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] A megathrust earthquake can produce sudden vertical displacement of a large area of ocean floor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Some of the deadliest natural disasters have occurred due to convergent boundary processes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami was triggered by a megathrust earthquake along the convergent boundary of the Indian plate and Burma microplate and killed over 200,000 people.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The 2011 tsunami off the coast of Japan, which caused 16,000 deaths and did US$360 billion in damage, was caused by a magnitude 9 megathrust earthquake along the convergent boundary of the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Accretionary wedges (also called accretionary prisms) form as sediment is scraped from the subducting lithosphere and emplaced against the overriding lithosphere.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] These sediments include igneous crust, turbidite sediments, and pelagic sediments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Imbricate thrust faulting along a basal decollement surface occurs in accretionary wedges as forces continue to compress and fault these newly added sediments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] The continued faulting of the accretionary wedge leads to overall thickening of the wedge.
[src:atlantic-ocean/active-margin] Seafloor topography plays some role in accretion, especially emplacement of igneous crust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The **Adriatic Sea** (/ˌeɪdriˈætɪk/) is a body of water separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic is the northernmost arm of the Mediterranean Sea, extending from the Strait of Otranto (where it connects to the Ionian Sea) to the northwest and the Po Valley.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The countries with coasts on the Adriatic are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Italy, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic contains more than 1,300 islands, mostly located along its eastern coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It is divided into three basins, the northern being the shallowest and the southern being the deepest, with a maximum depth of 1,233 metres (4,045 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The prevailing currents flow counterclockwise from the Strait of Otranto.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Tidal movements in the Adriatic are slight, although larger amplitudes occur occasionally.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's salinity is lower than the Mediterranean's because it collects a third of the fresh water flowing into the Mediterranean, acting as a dilution basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The surface water temperatures generally range from 30 °C (86 °F) in summer to 12 °C (54 °F) in winter, significantly moderating the Adriatic Basin's climate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea sits on the Apulian or Adriatic Microplate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the Italian Peninsula first formed, separating the Adriatic Basin from the rest of the Mediterranean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The western coast is alluvial or terraced, while the eastern coast is highly indented with pronounced karstification.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] There are dozens of marine protected areas in the Adriatic, designed to protect the sea's habitats and biodiversity—more than 7,000 species are identified as native to the Adriatic, many of them endemic, rare and threatened ones.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's shores are populated by more than 3.5 million people; the largest cities are Bari, Venice, Trieste and Split.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Early settlements on the Adriatic shores were Etruscan, Illyrian, and Greek.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] By the 2nd century BC, the region was under Rome's control.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Middle Ages, the sea was controlled, to a varying extent, by a series of states—most notably the Byzantine Empire, the Croatian Kingdom, the Republic of Venice, the Habsburg monarchy and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Napoleonic Wars resulted in the Austrian Empire gaining control of most of the eastern Adriatic shore and the Po Valley, while the Kingdom of Italy gradually took control of the remaining Italian coast during the 19th century.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Following the collapse of Austria-Hungary in 1918, control of the eastern coast passed to Yugoslavia and Albania, which agreed on their maritime boundaries with Italy in 1975 and 1992 respectively.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] After Yugoslavia's dissolution during the 1990s, its four coastal successor states—Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro—continued to recognise the previous maritime border with Italy, but have disputed the borders between themselves.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Fisheries and tourism are significant sources of income along the Adriatic coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Maritime transport is also a significant branch of the area's economy—there are 19 seaports in the Adriatic that each handle more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The largest Adriatic seaport by annual cargo turnover is the Port of Trieste, while the Port of Split is the largest by passengers served per year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The origins of the name *Adriatic* are linked to the Etruscan settlement of Adria, which probably derives its name from Illyrian *adur* 'water, sea'.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In classical antiquity, the sea was known as *Mare Adriaticum* (*Mare Hadriaticum*, also sometimes simplified to *Adria*) or, less frequently, as *Mare Superum* '[the] upper sea'.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The two terms were not synonymous, however.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] *Mare Adriaticum* generally corresponds to the Adriatic Sea's extent, spanning from the Gulf of Venice to the Strait of Otranto.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] That boundary became more consistently defined by Roman authors—early Greek sources place the boundary between the Adriatic and Ionian seas at various places ranging from adjacent to the Gulf of Venice to the southern tip of the Peloponnese, eastern shores of Sicily and western shores of Crete.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] *Mare Superum* on the other hand normally encompassed both the modern Adriatic Sea and the sea off the Apennine peninsula's southern coast, as far as the Strait of Sicily.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Another name used in the period was *Mare Dalmaticum*, applied to waters off the coast of Dalmatia or Illyricum.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] During the early modern period, the entire sea was also known as the **Gulf of Venice** (Italian: *golfo di Venezia*), although that name is now informally applied only to the northern area of the sea, from Maestra Point in the Po Delta to Cape Kamenjak on the Istrian Peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In Serbo-Croatian and Slovene, the sea is often referred to as simply *Jadran*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a semi-enclosed sea, bordered in the southwest by the Apennine or Italian Peninsula, in the northwest by the Italian regions of Veneto and Friuli-Venezia Giulia, and in the northeast by Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Albania—the Balkan peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the southeast, the Adriatic Sea connects to the Ionian Sea at the 72-kilometre (45 mi) wide Strait of Otranto.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It extends 800 kilometres (500 mi) from the northwest to the southeast and is 200 kilometres (120 mi) wide.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It covers 138,600 square kilometres (53,500 sq mi) and has a volume of 35,000 cubic kilometres (8,400 cu mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic extends northwest from 40° to 45°47' north, representing the Mediterranean's northernmost portion.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The sea is geographically divided into the Northern Adriatic, Central (or Middle) Adriatic, and Southern Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea drainage basin encompasses 235,000 square kilometres (91,000 sq mi), yielding a land–sea ratio of 1.8.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The drainage basin's mean elevation is 782 metres (2,566 ft) above sea level, with a mean slope of 12.1°.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Major rivers discharging into the Adriatic include the Po, Soča, Krka, Neretva, Drin, Buna, and Vjosë.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the late 19th century, Austria-Hungary established a geodetic network with an elevation benchmark using the average Adriatic Sea level at the Sartorio pier in Trieste, Italy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The benchmark was subsequently retained by Austria, adopted by Yugoslavia, and retained by the states that emerged after its dissolution.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In 2016, Slovenia adopted a new elevation benchmark referring to the upgraded tide gauge station in the coastal town of Koper.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Alps, which also have a large meteorological impact on the Mediterranean, touch the Adriatic in the area around Trieste towards Duino and Barcola.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea contains more than 1,300 islands and islets, most along the Adriatic's eastern coast—especially in Croatia, with 1,246 counted.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The number includes islands, islets, and rocks of all sizes, including ones emerging at ebb tide only.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian islands include the largest—Cres and Krk, each covering about the same area of 405.78 square kilometres (156.67 sq mi)—and the tallest—Brač, whose peak reaches 780 metres (2,560 ft) above sea level.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The islands of Cres and the adjacent Lošinj are separated only by a narrow navigable canal dug in the time of classical antiquity; the original single island was known to the Greeks as Apsyrtides.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian islands include 47 permanently inhabited ones, the most populous among them being Krk, Korčula and Brač.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The islands along the Adriatic's western (Italian) coast are smaller and less numerous than those along the opposite coast; the best-known ones are the 117 islands on which the city of Venice is built.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The northern shore of the Greek island of Corfu also lies in the Adriatic Sea as defined by the IHO.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The IHO boundary places the Diapontia Islands (northwest of Corfu) in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea's average depth is 259.5 metres (851 ft), and its maximum depth is 1,233 metres (4,045 ft); however, the North Adriatic basin rarely exceeds a depth of 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The North Adriatic basin, extending between Venice and Trieste towards a line connecting Ancona and Zadar, is only 15 metres (49 ft) deep at its northwestern end; it gradually deepens towards the southeast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It is the largest Mediterranean shelf and is simultaneously a dilution basin and a site of bottom water formation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Middle Adriatic basin is south of the Ancona–Zadar line, with the 270-metre (890 ft) deep Middle Adriatic Pit (also called the Pomo Depression or the Jabuka Pit).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The 170-metre (560 ft) deep Palagruža Sill is south of the Middle Adriatic Pit, separating it from the 1,200-metre (3,900 ft) deep South Adriatic Pit and the Middle Adriatic basin from the South Adriatic Basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Further on to the south, the sea floor rises to 780 metres (2,560 ft) to form the Otranto Sill at the boundary to the Ionian Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The South Adriatic Basin is similar in many respects to the Northern Ionian Sea, to which it is connected.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The coast's ruggedness is exacerbated by the Dinaric Alps' proximity to the coast, in contrast to the opposite (Italian) coast where the Apennine Mountains are further away from the shoreline.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The coastal water dynamics are determined by the asymmetric coasts and the inflow of the Mediterranean seawater through the Straits of Otranto and further on along the eastern coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The smooth Italian coast (with very few protrusions and no major islands) allows the Western Adriatic Current, which is composed of the relatively freshwater mass on the surface and the cold and dense water mass at the bottom, to flow smoothly.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The coastal currents on the opposite shore are far more complex owing to the jagged shoreline, several large islands and the proximity of the Dinaric Alps to the shore.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The last produces significant temperature variations between the sea and the hinterland, which leads to the creation of local jets.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The tidal movement is normally slight, usually remaining below 30 centimetres (12 in).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The amphidromic point is at the mid-width east of Ancona.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The normal tide levels are known to increase significantly in a conducive environment, leading to coastal flooding; this phenomenon is most famously known in Italy—especially Venice—as *acqua alta*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Such tides can exceed normal levels by more than 140 centimetres (55 in), with the highest tide level of 194 centimetres (76 in) observed on 4 November 1966.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Such flooding is caused by a combination of factors, including the alignment of the Sun and Moon, meteorological factors such as sirocco related storm surges, and the basin's geometric shape (which amplifies or reduces the astronomical component).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Moreover, the Adriatic's long and narrow rectangular shape is the source of an oscillating water motion (French: *seiche*) along the basin's minor axis.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Finally, Venice is increasingly vulnerable to flooding due to coastal area soil subsidence.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Such unusually high tides resulting in flooding have also been observed elsewhere in the Adriatic Sea, and have been recorded in recent years in the towns of Koper, Zadar and Šibenik as well.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that the Adriatic's entire volume is exchanged through the Strait of Otranto in 3.4±0.4 years, a comparatively short period.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] (For instance, approximately 500 years are necessary to exchange all the Black Sea's water.) This short period is particularly important as the rivers flowing into the Adriatic discharge up to 5,700 cubic metres per second (200,000 cu ft/s).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] This rate of discharge amounts to 0.5% of the total Adriatic Sea volume, or a 1.3-metre (4 ft 3 in) layer of water each year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The greatest portion of the discharge from any single river comes from the Po (28%), with an average discharge from it alone of 1,569 cubic metres per second (55,400 cu ft/s).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In terms of the annual total discharge into the entire Mediterranean Sea, the Po is ranked second, followed by the Neretva and Drin, which rank as third and fourth.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Another significant contributor of freshwater to the Adriatic is the submarine groundwater discharge through submarine springs (Croatian: *vrulja*); it is estimated to comprise 29% of the total water flux into the Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The submarine springs include thermal springs, discovered offshore near the town of Izola.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The thermal spring water is rich with hydrogen sulfide, has a temperature of 22 to 29.6 °C (71.6 to 85.3 °F), and has enabled the development of specific ecosystems.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The inflow of freshwater, representing a third of the freshwater volume flowing into the Mediterranean, makes the Adriatic a dilution basin for the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Middle and South Adriatic Gyres (SAG), are significant cyclonic circulation features, with the former being intermittent and the latter permanent.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The SAG measures 150 kilometres (93 miles) in diameter.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It contributes to the flow of bottom water from the Adriatic to the Levantine Basin through the Ionian Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Through that process, the Adriatic Sea produces most of the East Mediterranean deep water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's surface temperature usually ranges from 22 to 30 °C (72 to 86 °F) in the summer, or 12 to 14 °C (54 to 57 °F) in the winter, except along the western Adriatic coast's northern part, where it drops to 9 °C (48 °F) in the winter.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The distinct seasonal temperature variations, with a longitudinal gradient in the Northern and transversal gradient in the Middle and Southern Adriatic, are attributed to the continental characteristics of the Adriatic Sea: it is shallower and closer to land than are oceans.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] During particularly cold winters, sea ice may appear in the Adriatic's shallow coastal areas, especially in the Venetian Lagoon but also in isolated shallows as far south as Tisno (south of Zadar).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Southern Adriatic is about 8 to 10 °C (14 to 18 °F) warmer during the winter than the more northerly regions.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's salinity variation over the year is likewise distinct: it ranges between 38 and 39 PSUs, somewhat higher than the range of 32 to 37 PSUs for the open ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The southern Adriatic is subjected to saltier water from the Levantine Basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, the upper half of the Adriatic is classified as humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with wetter summers and colder and drier winters, and the southern Adriatic are classified as hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The air temperature can fluctuate by about 20 °C (36 °F) during a season.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The predominant winter winds are the bora and sirocco (called *jugo* along the eastern coast).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The bora is significantly conditioned by wind gaps in the Dinaric Alps bringing cold and dry continental air; it reaches peak speeds in the areas of Trieste, Senj, and Split, with gusts of up to 180 kilometres per hour (97 kn; 110 mph).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The sirocco brings humid and warm air, often carrying Saharan sand causing rain dust.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] On the Adriatic Sea's coasts and islands, there are numerous small settlements and a number of larger cities.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Among the largest are (counterclockwise) Trieste, Venice, Rimini, Ancona, Pescara and Bari in Italy; Vlorë and Durrës in Albania; Split, Zadar and Rijeka in Croatia; Koper in Slovenia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In total, more than 3.5 million people live on the Adriatic coasts.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] There are also some larger cities that are located very near the coast, such as the Italian cities of Ravenna and Lecce.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Venice, which was originally built on islands off the coast, is most at risk due to subsidence, but the threat is present in the Po delta as well.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The causes are a decrease in sedimentation rate due to loss of sediment behind dams, the deliberate excavation of sand for industrial purposes, agricultural use of water, and removal of ground water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The sinking of Venice slowed after artesian wells were banned in the 1960s, but the city remains threatened by the *acqua alta* floods.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Recent studies have suggested that the city is no longer sinking, but a state of alert remains in place.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In May 2003, then-Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi inaugurated the MOSE project (Italian: *Modulo Sperimentale Elettromeccanico*), an experimental model for evaluating the performance of inflatable gates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The project proposes laying a series of 79 inflatable pontoons across the sea bed at the three entrances to the Venetian Lagoon.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] When tides are predicted to rise above 110 centimetres (43 in), the pontoons will be filled with air and block the incoming water from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] This engineering work was due to be completed by 2014, but as of November 2020 is expected to be completed in 2021.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] However, concern has been raised regarding the frequency of its use—while only necessary a few days a year, the worst-case sea level rise scenario between 2050 and 2100 would prompt deployment up to 187 days a year, essentially cutting off the Venetian Lagoon from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Among other possible adverse effects, this can be expected to lower the lagoon's oxygen levels and trap pollution inside of the city.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Geophysical and geological information indicate that the Adriatic Sea and the Po Valley are associated with a tectonic microplate—identified as the Apulian or Adriatic Plate—that separated from the African Plate during the Mesozoic era.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] This separation began in the Middle and Late Triassic, when limestone began to be deposited in the area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Between the Norian and Late Cretaceous, the Adriatic and Apulia Carbonate Platforms formed as a thick series of carbonate sediments (dolomites and limestones), up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) deep.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Remnants of the former are found in the Adriatic Sea, as well as in the southern Alps and the Dinaric Alps, and remnants of the latter are seen as the Gargano Promontory and the Maiella mountain.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Eocene and early Oligocene, the plate moved north and north-east, contributing to the Alpine orogeny (along with the African and Eurasian Plates' movements) via the tectonic uplift of the Dinarides and Alps.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the motion was reversed and the Apennine Mountains' orogeny took place.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] An unbroken zone of increased seismic activity borders the Adriatic Sea, with a belt of thrust faults generally oriented in the northeast–southwest direction on the east coast and the northeast–southwest normal faults in the Apennines, indicating an Adriatic counterclockwise rotation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] An active 200-kilometre (120 mi) fault has been identified to the northwest of Dubrovnik, adding to the Dalmatian islands as the Eurasian Plate slides over the Adriatic microplate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Furthermore, the fault causes the Apennine peninsula's southern tip to move towards the opposite shore by about 0.4 centimetres (0.16 in) per year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] If this movement continues, the seafloor will be completely consumed and the Adriatic Sea closed off in 50–70 million years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Northern Adriatic, the coast of the Gulf of Trieste and western Istria is gradually subsiding, having sunk about 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in) in the past two thousand years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Middle Adriatic Basin, there is evidence of Permian volcanism in the area of Komiža on the island of Vis and the volcanic islands of Jabuka and Brusnik.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Earthquakes have been observed in the region since the earliest historical records.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] A recent strong earthquake in the region was the 1979 Montenegro earthquake, measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Historical earthquakes in the area include the 1627 Gargano peninsula and the 1667 Dubrovnik earthquakes, both followed by strong tsunamis.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the last 600 years, fifteen tsunamis have occurred in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] All types of seafloor sediments are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Northern Adriatic's comparatively shallow seabed is characterised by relict sand (from times when the water level was lower and the area was a sandy beach), while a muddy bed is typical at depths below 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Sediments deposited in the Adriatic Sea today generally come from the northwest coast, being carried by the Po, Reno, Adige, Brenta, Tagliamento, Piave and Soča rivers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The volume of sediments carried from the eastern shore by the Rječina, Zrmanja, Krka, Cetina, Ombla, Dragonja, Mirna, Raša and Neretva rivers is negligible, because these sediments are mostly deposited at the river mouths.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic's western shores are largely either alluvial or terraced, whereas the eastern shores are predominantly rocky, except for the southernmost part of the shore located in Albania that consists of sandy coves and rocky capes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The eastern Adriatic shore's Croatian part is the most indented Mediterranean coastline.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Most of the eastern coast is characterised by a karst topography, developed from the Adriatic Carbonate Platform's exposure to weathering.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Karstification there largely began after the Dinarides' final uplift in the Oligocene and the Miocene, when carbonate deposits were exposed to atmospheric effects; this extended to the level of 120 metres (390 ft) below the present sea level, exposed during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that some karst formations are from earlier sea level drops, most notably the Messinian salinity crisis.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Similarly, karst developed in Apulia from the Apulian Carbonate Platform.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Rocks of the same type are found in Albania and on the western Adriatic coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] There are alternations of maritime and alluvial sediments occurring in the Po Valley, at the Adriatic's north-west coast, and as far west as Piacenza, dating to the Pleistocene as the sea advanced and receded over the valley.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] An advance began after the Last Glacial Maximum, which brought the Adriatic to a high point at about 5,500 years ago.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Since then, the Po delta has been prograding (expanding/extending).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The rate of coastal zone progradation between 1000 BC and 1200 AD was 4 metres (13 ft) per year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the 12th century, the delta advanced at a rate of 25 metres (82 ft) per year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the 17th century, the delta began to become a human-controlled environment, as the excavation of artificial channels started; the channels and new distributaries of the Po have been prograding at rates of 50 metres (160 ft) per year or more since then.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] There are more than 20 other rivers flowing into the Adriatic Sea in Italy alone, also forming alluvial coastlines, including the lagoons of Venice, Grado and Caorle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] There are smaller eastern Adriatic alluvial coasts—in the deltas of the Dragonja, Buna and Neretva rivers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a unique water body in respect of its overall biogeochemical physiognomy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It exports inorganic nutrients and imports particulate organic carbon and nitrogen through the Strait of Otranto—acting as a mineralization site.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The exchange of the substances is made more complex by bathymetry of the Adriatic Sea—75% of water flowing north through the strait recirculates at the Palagruža Sill and North Adriatic adds no more than 3–4% of water to the South Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] This is reflected in its biogeography and ecology, and particularly in the composition and properties of its ecosystems.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Its main biogeographic units are the Northern Adriatic, the Central Adriatic, and the Southern Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The unique nature of the Adriatic gives rise to an abundance of endemic flora and fauna.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Croatian National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan identified more than 7,000 animal and plant species in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Central Adriatic is especially abundant in endemic plant species, with 535 identified species of green, brown and red algae.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Four out of five Mediterranean seagrass species are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The most common species are *Cymodocea nodosa* and *Zostera noltii*, while *Zostera marina* and *Posidonia oceanica* are comparatively rare.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] This circulation has significantly contributed to the biodiversity of the countries along the eastern Adriatic coast; the common bottlenose dolphin is frequent in the eastern coast's waters only, and the Croatian coast provides refuge for the critically endangered monk seal and sea turtles.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Recent studies revealed that cetaceans and other marine megafaunas, that were once thought to be vagrants to Adriatic Sea, migrate and live in the semi-closed sea on larger scales.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Largest of these live normally is the fin whale, and sperm whale, the largest of toothed whales also migrate but less common than fin whales, followed by Cuvier's beaked whales.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Basking sharks and manta rays are some of migrant species to the sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Historical presences of depleted or extinct species such as North Atlantic right whales (extinct or functionally extinct), Atlantic gray whales (extinct), and humpback whales have been speculated as well.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Tuna has been caught by the locals in the upper Adriatic for thousands of years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The very large schools consisted mainly of little tunny and moved as far as the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] However, increasing fishing prevented the migration of large schools of fish to the north.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The last major tuna catch was made there in 1954 by the fishermen from Santa Croce, Contovello and Barcola.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Northern Adriatic in particular is rich in endemic fish fauna.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Around thirty species of fish are found in only one or two countries bordering the Adriatic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] These are particularly due to or dependent upon the karst morphology of the coastal or submarine topography; this includes inhabiting subterranean habitats, karst rivers, and areas around freshwater springs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] There are 45 known subspecies endemic to the Adriatic's coasts and islands.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In the Adriatic, there are at least 410 species and subspecies of fish, representing approximately 70% of Mediterranean taxa, with at least 7 species endemic to the Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Sixty-four known species are threatened with extinction, largely because of overfishing.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Only a small fraction of the fish found in the Adriatic are attributed to recent processes such as Lessepsian migration, and escape from mariculture.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The biodiversity of the Adriatic is relatively high, and several marine protected areas have been established by countries along its coasts.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In Italy, these are Miramare in the Gulf of Trieste (in the Northern Adriatic), Torre del Cerrano and Tremiti Islands in the Middle Adriatic basin and Torre Guaceto in southern Apulia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Miramare protected area was established in 1986 and covers 30 hectares (74 acres) of coast and 90 hectares (220 acres) of sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The area encompasses 1.8 kilometres (1.1 mi) of coastline near the Miramare promontory in the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Torre del Cerrano protected area was created in 2009, extending 3 nautical miles (5.6 km; 3.5 mi) into the sea and along 7 kilometres (4.3 mi) of coastline.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Various zones of the protected area cover 37 square kilometres (14 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Tremiti Islands reserve has been protected since 1989, while the Tremiti islands themselves are part of the Gargano National Park.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Torre Guaceto protected area, located near Brindisi and Carovigno, covers a sea surface of 2,227 hectares (5,500 acres) and is adjacent to the Torre Guaceto State Reserve covering 1,114 hectares (2,750 acres) of coast and sharing an 8-kilometre (5.0 mi) coastline with the marine protected area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Furthermore, there are 10 internationally important (Ramsar) wetland reserves in Italy located along the Adriatic coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Brijuni national park encompasses the 743.3-hectare (1,837-acre) archipelago itself and 2,651.7 hectares (6,552 acres) of surrounding sea; it became a national park in 1999.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Lim Canal is a 10-kilometre (6.2 mi) ria of the Pazinčica river.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Kornati national park was established in 1980; it covers approximately 220 square kilometres (85 sq mi), including 89 islands and islets.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The marine environment encompasses three-quarters of the total area, while the island shores' combined length equals 238 kilometres (148 mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Telašćica is a nature park established on Dugi Otok in 1988.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The park covers 69 kilometres (43 mi) of coastline, 22.95 square kilometres (8.86 sq mi) of land and 44.55 square kilometres (17.20 sq mi) of sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Bay of Mali Ston is located at the border of Croatia and Bosnia–Herzegovina, north of the Pelješac peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The marine protected area covers 48 square kilometres (19 sq mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Lastovo nature park was established in 2006, and it includes 44 islands and islets, 53 square kilometres (20 sq mi) of land and 143 square kilometres (55 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Mljet national park was established in 1960, covering a 24-square-kilometre (9.3 sq mi) marine protection area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In addition, there is a Ramsar wetland reserve in Croatia—the Neretva river's delta.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In Slovenia, the marine and coastal protected nature areas are the Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park, Strunjan Landscape Park, Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve, and the Debeli Rtič, Cape Madona and Lakes in Fiesa natural monuments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park was established in 1990, covers 721 hectares (1,780 acres), and includes four nature reserves.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In 1993, the area was designated a Ramsar site; it is also a site of international importance for waterbird species.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The 429-hectare (1,060-acre) Strunjan Landscape Park was established in 2004 and comprises two nature reserves.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It includes a 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) long cliff, the northernmost Mediterranean salt field and the only Slovenian lagoon system.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It is also the northernmost point of growth of some Mediterranean plant species.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve was established in 1998 and covers 122 hectares (300 acres).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Debeli Rtič natural monument covers 24 hectares (59 acres), the Cape Madona natural monument covers 12 hectares (30 acres), and the Lakes in Fiesa natural monument, with the coastal lake as the only brackish lake in Slovenia, covers 2.1 hectares (5.2 acres).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In 2010, Albania established its first marine protection area, the Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park at the Karaburun Peninsula where the Adriatic and Ionian Seas meet.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The park covers a total of 12,570 hectares (31,100 acres).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Two additional marine protection areas are planned in Albania: the Cape of Rodon (Albanian: *Kepi i Rodonit*) and Porto Palermo.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] In addition, Albania is home to two Ramsar wetland reserves: Karavasta Lagoon, and Butrint.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Neither Bosnia–Herzegovina nor Montenegro have or plan to establish any marine protection areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Adriatic Sea ecosystem is threatened by excessive input of nutrients through drainage from agricultural land and wastewater flowing from cities; this includes both along its coast and from rivers draining into the sea—especially from the Po River.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Venice is often cited as an example of polluted coastal waters where shipping, transportation, farming, manufacturing and wastewater disposal contribute to polluting the sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] A further risk is presented by ballast water discharge by ships, especially tankers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Still, since most of the cargo handled by the Adriatic ports, and virtually all liquid (tanker) cargo handled by the ports, is coming to—not coming from—the Adriatic Basin, the risk from ballast water (from tankers expelling ballast water then loading in the Adriatic) remains minimal.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] However, proposed export oil pipelines were objected to specifically because of this issue.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Oil spills are a major concern in terms of potential environmental impact and damage to tourism and fisheries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] It is estimated that if a major oil spill happened, a million people would lose their livelihoods in Croatia alone.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] An additional risk is presented by oil refineries in the Po River basin where oil spills have occurred before, in addition to accidents occurring in the Adriatic already, so far with no significant environmental consequences.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Since 2006, Italy has been considering the construction of an offshore and an onshore LNG terminal in the Gulf of Trieste, as well as a pipeline, in the immediate vicinity of the Slovenian–Italian border.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] The Slovenian government and municipalities, the municipal council of Trieste, and non-governmental organisations have voiced concern over their environmental hazards, effect on transport and effect on tourism.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Another source of pollution of the Adriatic is solid waste.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Drifting waste—occasionally relatively large quantities of material, especially waste plastic—is transported northwest by the sirocco.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Air pollution in the Adriatic Basin is associated with the large industrial centres in the Po River valley and the large industrial cities along the coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Italy and Yugoslavia established a joint commission to protect the Adriatic Sea from pollution in 1977; the organization later changed with Slovenia, Croatia and Montenegro replacing Yugoslavia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] Future pollution hazards are addressed and pollution hotspots are assessed not only by nations in the basin but also through regional projects with World Bank support.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p01] 27 such hotspots have been determined as of 2011, 6 warranting an urgent response.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Settlements along the Adriatic dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC appear in Albania and Dalmatia on the eastern Adriatic coast, related to the Cardium pottery culture.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During classical antiquity, Illyrians inhabited the eastern coast, and the western coast was inhabited by the peoples of Ancient Italy, mainly Etruscans, before the Roman Republic's rise.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Greek colonisation of the Adriatic dates back to the 7th and 6th centuries BC when the ancient cities of Epidamnos and Apollonia were founded.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Greeks soon expanded further north establishing several cities, including Ancona, Black Corcyra, Epidaurus, Issa, with trade established as far north as the Po River delta, where an emporium (trading station) was founded in Adria.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Roman economic and military influence in the region began to grow with the creation by 246 BC of a major naval base at Brundisium (now Brindisi), which was established to bar Carthaginian ships from the Adriatic during the Punic Wars.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] This led to conflict with the Illyrians, who lived in a collection of semi-Hellenized kingdoms that covered much of the Balkans and controlled the eastern shore of the sea, resulting in the Illyrian Wars from 229 to 168 BC.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The initial Roman intervention in 229 BC, motivated in part by a desire to suppress Illyrian piracy in the Adriatic, marked the first time that the Roman navy crossed that sea to launch a military campaign.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Those wars ended with the eastern shore becoming a province of the Roman Republic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] However, resistance to Roman rule continued sporadically and Rome did not completely consolidate control of the region until Augustus's general Tiberius put down the Great Illyrian Revolt, a bitter struggle waged from 6 to 9 AD.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the repression of the revolt the Roman province of Illyricum was split into Dalmatia and Pannonia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During the Roman period, Brundisium, on the western shore, and Apollonia and Dyrrachium (originally called Epidamnos, now Durrës in Albania) on the eastern shore became important ports.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Brundisium was linked by the Via Appia road to the city of Rome, and Dyrrachium and Apollonia were both on the Via Egnatia, a road that by about 130 BC the Romans had extended eastward across the Balkans to Byzantium (later Constantinople, now Istanbul).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] This made the sea passage across the Adriatic between Brundisium and Dyrrachium (or Apollonia) a link in the primary route for travelers, trade, and troop movements, between Rome and the East.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] This route played a major role in some of the military operations that marked the end of the Roman Republic and the start of the imperial period.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Sulla used it during the First Mithridatic War.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Marc Antony and Octavian (later Augustus) crossed the Adriatic to Dyrrachium with their armies in their campaign against two of Caesar's assassins, Brutus and Cassius, that culminated in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Brundisium and Dyrrachium remained important ports well after the Roman period, but an earthquake in the 3rd century AD changed the path of a river causing Apollonia's harbor to silt up, and the city to decline.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Another city on the Italian coast of the Adriatic that increased in importance during the Roman era was Ravenna.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During the reign of Augustus, it became a major naval base as part of his program to re-organize the Roman navy to better protect commerce in the Mediterranean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During the 4th century AD the emperors of the Western Roman Empire had moved their official residence north from Rome to Mediolanum (now Milan) in order to be better able to control the military frontier with the Germanic tribes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 402 AD, during a period of repeated Germanic invasions of Italy, the capital was shifted to Ravenna because nearby marshes made it more defensible, and the Adriatic provided an easy escape path by sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] When the Western Empire fell in 476 AD Ravenna became the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Early Middle Ages, after the Roman Empire's decline, the Adriatic's coasts were ruled by Ostrogoths, Lombards and the Byzantine Empire.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ostrogothic Kingdom ruled Italy following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 AD.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] However, during the reign of Justinian the Byzantine Empire sent an army under the general Belisarius to regain control of Italy, resulting in the Gothic War (535–554).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Byzantines established the Exarchate of Ravenna and by 553 AD their viceroy (Exarch) ruled almost the entire Italian peninsula from that city.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 568 AD the Lombards invaded northern Italy, and over the course of the next century or so the importance of the Exarchate declined as the territory under Lombard control expanded and as the Byzantine outpost of Venice became increasingly independent.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 752 AD the Lombards overthrew the Exarchate, ending the influence of the Byzantine Empire on the western shore of the Adriatic for a few centuries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Republic of Venice, one of the maritime republics, was founded during this period and went on to become a significant maritime power after receiving a Byzantine tax exemption in 1082.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The end of the period brought about the Holy Roman Empire's control over the Kingdom of Italy (which would last until the Peace of Westphalia in 1648), the establishment of an independent Kingdom of Croatia and the Byzantine Empire's return to the southern Apennine peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In addition, the Papal States were carved out in the area around Rome and central Italy in the 8th century.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In this period, the Republic of Venice began to expand its territory and influence.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1202, the Fourth Crusade was diverted to conquer Zadar at the behest of the Venetians—the first instance of a Crusader force attacking a Catholic city—before proceeding to sack Constantinople.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the 13th century, Venice established itself as a leading maritime nation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During much of the 12th and 13th centuries, Venice and the Republic of Genoa were engaged in warfare culminating in the War of Chioggia, ousting the Genoese from the Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Still, the 1381 Treaty of Turin that ended the war required Venice to renounce claims to Dalmatia, after losing the territory to Hungary in 1358.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the same year, the Republic of Ragusa was established in Dubrovnik as a city-state after it was freed from Venetian suzerainty.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Venice regained Dalmatia in 1409 and held it for nearly four hundred years, with the republic's apex of trading and military power in the first half of the 15th century.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] These defeats spelled the end of an independent Hungarian kingdom, and both Croatian and Hungarian nobility chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as their new ruler, bringing the Habsburg monarchy to the shore of the Adriatic Sea, where it would remain for nearly four hundred years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ottomans and Venetians fought a series of wars, but until the 17th century these were not fought in the Adriatic area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Ottoman raids on the Adriatic coasts effectively ceased after the massive setback in the Battle of Lepanto in October 1571.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The 17th century's final territorial changes were caused by the Morean or Sixth Ottoman–Venetian War, when in 1699 Venice slightly enlarged its possessions in Dalmatia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1797, the Republic of Venice was abolished after the French conquest.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Venetian territory was then handed over to Austria and briefly ruled as part of the Archduchy of Austria.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The territory was turned back over to France after the Peace of Pressburg in 1805 when the territory in the Po valley became an integral part of the new Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The new kingdom included the province of Romagna, thus removing the Papal State from the Adriatic coast; however, Trieste, Istria and Dalmatia were joined into a set of separate provinces of the French Empire: the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] These were created in 1809 through the Treaty of Schönbrunn; they represented the end of Venetian rule on the eastern Adriatic coast, as well as the end of the Republic of Ragusa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Sea was a minor theatre in the Napoleonic Wars; the Adriatic campaign of 1807–1814 involved the Royal Navy contesting the Adriatic's control by the combined navies of France, Italy and the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During the campaign, the British navy occupied Vis and established its base there in Port St.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The campaign reached its climax in the 1811 Battle of Lissa, and ended with British and Austrian forces seizing the coastal cities on the eastern Adriatic coast from the French.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Days before the Battle of Waterloo, the Congress of Vienna awarded the Illyrian Provinces (spanning from the Gulf of Trieste to the Bay of Kotor) to Austria.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Congress of Vienna also created the Kingdom of Lombardy–Venetia which encompassed the city of Venice, the surrounding coast and a substantial hinterland, and was controlled by Austria.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Apennine peninsula's south, the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was formed in 1816 by unifying the kingdoms of Naples and Sicily.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The process of Italian unification culminated in the Second Italian War of Independence, resulting in the Kingdom of Sardinia annexing all territories along the western Adriatic coast south of Venetia in 1860, and the 1861 establishment of the Kingdom of Italy in its place.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Kingdom of Italy expanded in 1866: it annexed Venetia, but its navy was defeated in the Adriatic near Vis.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 and the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868, the control of much of the eastern Adriatic coast was redefined.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The cisleithanian (Austrian) part of Austria-Hungary spanned from the Austrian Littoral to the Bay of Kotor, with the exception of the Croatian Littoral mainland.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the territory outside the Austrian Littoral, special status was given to Fiume (modern-day Rijeka) as a separate part of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The rest of the territory was made a part of the Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia, which in turn was also in the Transleithanian part of the dual monarchy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic coastline controlled by the Ottoman Empire was reduced by the Congress of Berlin in 1878, through recognition of the independence of the Principality of Montenegro, which controlled the coast south of the Bay of Kotor to the Bojana River.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Ottoman Empire lost all territories along the Adriatic following the First Balkan War and consequent 1913 Treaty of London that established an independent Albania.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The World War I Adriatic Campaign was largely limited to blockade attempts by the Allies and the effort of the Central Powers to thwart the British, French and Italian moves.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Italy joined the Allies in April 1915 with the Treaty of London, which promised Italy the Austrian Littoral, northern Dalmatia, the port of Vlorë, most of the eastern Adriatic islands and Albania as a protectorate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The treaty provided the basis for all the following divisions between Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1918, the Montenegrin national assembly voted to unite with the Kingdom of Serbia, giving the latter access to the Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Another short-lived, unrecognised state established in 1918 was the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs, formed from parts of Austria-Hungary, comprising most of the former monarchy's Adriatic coastline.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Later that year, the Kingdom of Serbia and the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs formed the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes—subsequently renamed Yugoslavia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The proponents of the new union in the Croatian parliament saw the move as a safeguard against Italian expansionism as stipulated in the Treaty of London.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The treaty was largely disregarded by Britain and France because of conflicting promises made to Serbia and a perceived lack of Italian contribution to the war effort outside Italy itself.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The 1919 Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye did transfer the Austrian Littoral and Istria to Italy but awarded Dalmatia to Yugoslavia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Following the war, a private force of demobilized Italian soldiers seized Rijeka and set up the Italian Regency of Carnaro—seen as a harbinger of Fascism—in order to force the recognition of Italian claims to the city.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During World War II, the Adriatic saw only limited naval action, starting with the Italian invasion of Albania and the joint Axis invasion of Yugoslavia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The latter led to the annexation of a large part of Dalmatia and nearly all the eastern Adriatic islands by Italy and the establishment of two puppet states, the Independent State of Croatia and the Kingdom of Montenegro, which controlled the remainder of the former Yugoslav Adriatic coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 1947, after the Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces and the war's end, Italy (now a republic) and the Allies signed the Treaty of Peace with Italy.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The FTT was partitioned in 1954: Trieste itself and the area to the North of it were placed under Italian control, while the rest came under Yugoslav control.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] This arrangement was made permanent in the 1975 Treaty of Osimo.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] During the Cold War, the Adriatic Sea became the southernmost flank of the Iron Curtain as Italy joined NATO, while the Warsaw Pact established bases in Albania.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] After the fall of communism, Yugoslavia broke apart: Slovenia and Croatia declared independence in 1991, and Bosnia–Herzegovina followed in 1992, while Montenegro remained in a federation with Serbia, officially called Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The ensuing Croatian War of Independence included limited naval engagements and a blockade of Croatia's coast by the Yugoslav Navy, leading to the Battle of the Dalmatian channels and a later withdrawal of Yugoslav vessels.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Montenegro declared itself independent in 2006, effectively land-locking Serbia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The period also saw the Adriatic Sea as the theatre of several NATO operations, including the blockade of Yugoslavia, intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina and the 1999 bombing of Yugoslavia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Italy and Yugoslavia defined their Adriatic continental shelf delimitation in 1968, with an additional agreement signed in 1975 on the Gulf of Trieste boundary, following the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The boundary agreed in 1968 extends 353 nautical miles (654 km; 406 mi) and consists of 43 points connected by straight lines or circular arc segments.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The additional boundary agreed upon in 1975 consists of 5 points, extending from an end point of the 1968 line.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] All successor states of former Yugoslavia accepted the agreements.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the Adriatic's southernmost areas the border was not determined in order to avoid prejudicing the location of the tripoint with the Albanian continental shelf border, which remains undefined.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Before the breakup of Yugoslavia, Albania, Italy and Yugoslavia initially proclaimed 15-nautical-mile (28 km; 17 mi) territorial waters, subsequently reduced to international-standard 12 nautical miles (22 km; 14 mi) and all sides adopted baseline systems (mostly in the 1970s).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Albania and Italy determined their sea border in 1992 according to the equidistance principle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Following Croatian EU membership, the Adriatic became an internal sea of the EU.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea defines the Adriatic Sea as an enclosed or semi-enclosed sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Euroregion was established in Pula in 2006 to promote trans-regional and trans-national cooperation in the Adriatic Sea area and serve as an Adriatic framework to help resolve issues of regional importance.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In addition, the maritime boundary between Albania and Montenegro was not defined before the 1990s.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia and Slovenia started negotiations to define maritime borders in the Gulf of Piran in 1992 but failed to agree, resulting in a dispute.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Both countries also declared their economic zones, which partially overlap.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia's application to become an EU member state was initially suspended pending resolution of its border disputes with Slovenia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] These disputes with Slovenia were eventually settled with an agreement to accept the decision of an international arbitration commission set up via the UN, enabling Croatia to progress towards EU membership.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia is still not following the resolution of the international arbitration for the Gulf of Piran.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] A dispute over the gulf is still on going with the Croatians handing out fines to Slovenian fishermen that are following the agreed economic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Aside from the EU membership difficulty, even before its settling the dispute has caused no major practical problems.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The maritime boundary between Bosnia–Herzegovina and Croatia was formally settled in 1999, but a few issues are still in dispute—the Klek peninsula and two islets in the border area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Croatia–Montenegro maritime boundary is disputed in the Bay of Kotor, at the Prevlaka peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] This dispute was exacerbated by the peninsula's occupation by the Yugoslav People's Army and later by the (Serbian–Montenegrin) FR Yugoslav Army, which in turn was replaced by a United Nations observer mission that lasted until 2002.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatia took over the area with an agreement that allowed Montenegrin presence in the bay's Croatian waters, and the dispute has become far less contentious since Montenegro's independence in 2006.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic Sea fishery's production is distributed among countries in the basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2000, the nominal—on a live weight basis—total landings of all Adriatic fisheries reached 110,000 tonnes (108,000 long tons).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Overfishing is a recognised problem—450 species of fish live in the Adriatic Sea, including 120 species threatened by excessive commercial fishing, a problem exacerbated by pollution and global warming.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Overexploited species include common dentex, red scorpionfish, monkfish, John Dory, blue shark, spiny dogfish, mullet, red mullet, Norway lobster, as well as European hake, and sardines.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Turtles and common bottlenose dolphins are also being killed by fishing nets.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The depleted fish stock, and Croatia's Ecological and Fisheries Protection Zone (ZERP) contributed to accusations of overfishing exchanged between Italian and Croatian fishermen.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] ZERP was introduced in 2003, but its application to EU member states was suspended in 2004.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The depleted stocks of fish are being addressed through a new proposed EU fisheries policy that was scheduled to take effect in 2013, when Croatia acceded to the EU, and restore the stocks to sustainable levels by 2015.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest volume of fish harvesting was in Italy, where the total production volume in 2007 stood at 465,637 tonnes (458,283 long tons).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2003, 28.8% of Italian fisheries production volume was generated in the Northern and central Adriatic, and 24.5% in Apulia (from the Southern Adriatic and Ionian Sea).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Italian fisheries, including those operating outside the Adriatic, employed 60,700 in the primary sector, including aquaculture (which comprises 40% of the total fisheries production).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The total fisheries output's gross value in 2002 was $1.9 billion.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, Croatia's production in live weight reached 53,083 tonnes (52,245 long tons).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2006, the total Croatian fisheries production volume was 37,800 tonnes (37,200 long tons) of catch and 14,200 tonnes (14,000 long tons) from marine aquaculture.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatian fisheries employed approximately 20,000.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Croatian marine aquaculture production consisted of tuna (47.2%), oysters and mussels (28.2% combined) and bass and bream (24.6% combined).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, Albanian fisheries production amounted to 7,505 tonnes (7,386 long tons), including aquaculture production, which reached 1,970 tonnes (1,940 long tons) in 2006.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] At the same time, Slovenian fisheries produced a total of 2,500 tonnes (2,460 long tons) with 55% of the production volume originating in aquaculture, representing the highest ratio in the Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Finally, the Montenegrin fisheries production stood at 911 tonnes (897 long tons) in 2006, with only 11 tonnes coming from aquaculture.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2007, the fisheries production in Bosnia–Herzegovina reached volume of 9,625 and 2,463 tonnes (9,473 and 2,424 long tons) in Slovenia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The countries bordering the Adriatic Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest number of tourist overnight stays and the most numerous tourist accommodation facilities are recorded in Italy, especially in the Veneto region (around Venice).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Veneto is followed by the Emilia-Romagna region and by the Adriatic Croatian counties.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Croatian tourist facilities are further augmented by 21,000 nautical ports and moorings; nautical tourists are attracted to various types of marine protected areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] As of January 2012, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 103 Italian Adriatic beaches and 29 marinas, 116 Croatian beaches and 19 marinas, 7 Slovenian beaches and 2 marinas, and 16 Montenegrin beaches.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Adriatic tourism is a significant source of income for these countries, especially in Croatia and Montenegro where the tourism income generated along the Adriatic coast represents the bulk of such income.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The direct contribution of travel and tourism to Croatia's GDP stood at 5.1% in 2011, with the total industry contribution estimated at 12.8% of the national GDP.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] For Montenegro, the direct contribution of tourism to the national GDP is 8.1%, with the total contribution to the economy at 17.2% of Montenegrin GDP.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Tourism in Adriatic Croatia has recently exhibited greater growth than in the other regions around the Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] There are nineteen Adriatic Sea ports (in four different countries) that each handles more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest cargo ports among them are the Port of Trieste (the largest Adriatic cargo port in Italy), the Port of Venice, the Port of Ravenna, the Port of Koper (the largest Slovenian port), the Port of Rijeka (the largest Croatian cargo port), and the Port of Brindisi.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest passenger ports in the Adriatic are the Port of Split (the largest Croatian passenger port) and ports in Ancona (the largest Italian passenger seaport in the Adriatic).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The largest seaport in Montenegro is the Port of Bar.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2010, the Northern Adriatic seaports of Trieste, Venice, Ravenna, Koper and Rijeka founded the North Adriatic Ports Association to position themselves more favourably in the EU's transport systems.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The port of Trieste is of particular importance for Central Europe because this is where the Transalpine Pipeline begins, supplying 100 percent of southern Germany, 90 percent of Austria and 50 percent of the Czech Republic with crude oil.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Natural gas is produced through several projects, including a joint venture of the Eni and INA companies that operates two platforms—one is in Croatian waters and draws gas from six wells, and the other (which started operating in 2010) is located in Italian waters.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The Adriatic gas fields were discovered in the 1970s, but their development commenced in 1996.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In 2008, INA produced 14.58 million BOE per day of gas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] About 100 offshore platforms are located in the Emilia-Romagna region, along with 17 in the Northern Adriatic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Eni estimated its concessions in the Adriatic Sea to hold at least 40,000,000,000 cubic metres (1.4×1012 cu ft) of natural gas, adding that they may even reach 100,000,000,000 cubic metres (3.5×1012 cu ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] INA estimates, however, are 50% lower than those supplied by Eni.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Oil was discovered in the Northern Adriatic at a depth of approximately 5,400 metres (17,700 ft); the discovery was assessed as not viable because of its location, depth and quality.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] These gas and oil reserves are part of the Po basin Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Mediterranean Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In the 2000s, investigation works aimed at discovering gas and oil reserves in the Middle and Southern Adriatic basins intensified, and by the decade's end, oil and natural gas reserves were discovered southeast of the Bari, Brindisi—Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Surveys indicate reserves of 3 billion barrels of oil in place and 5.7×1010 cubic metres (2,000,000,000,000 cu ft) of gas in place.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] The discovery was followed by further surveys off the Croatian coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] In January 2012, INA commenced prospecting for oil off Dubrovnik, marking the resumption of oil exploration along the eastern Adriatic coast after surveys commenced in the late 1980s around the island of Brač were cancelled because of Yugoslavia's breakup and war in Croatia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] Montenegro is also expected to look for oil off its coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/adriatic-sea-p02] As of January 2012, only 200 exploration wells had been sunk off the Croatian coast, with all but 30 in the Northern Adriatic basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The **Atlantic Ocean** is the second largest of the world's five oceanic divisions, with an area of about 85,133,000 square kilometers (32,870,000 sq mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] It covers approximately 17% of Earth's surface and about 24% of its water surface area.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Age of Discovery, it was known for separating the New World of the Americas (North America and South America) from the Old World of Afro-Eurasia (Africa, Asia, and Europe).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Through its separation of Afro-Eurasia from the Americas, the Atlantic Ocean has played a central role in the development of human society, globalization, and the histories of many nations.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] While the Norse were the first known humans to cross the Atlantic, it was the expedition of Christopher Columbus in 1492 that proved to be the most consequential.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Columbus's expedition ushered in an age of exploration and colonization of the Americas by European powers, most notably Portugal, Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] From the 16th to 19th centuries, the Atlantic Ocean was the center of both an eponymous slave trade and the Columbian exchange while occasionally hosting naval battles.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Such naval battles, as well as growing trade from regional American powers like the United States and Brazil, both increased in degree during the early 20th century.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] After World War II, major military operations became rarer, though notable postwar conflicts include the Cuban Missile Crisis and the Falklands War.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The ocean remains a core component of trade around the world.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean's temperatures vary by location.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] For example, the South Atlantic maintains warm temperatures year-round, as its basin countries are tropical.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The North Atlantic maintains a temperate climate, as its basin countries are temperate and have seasons of extremely low temperatures and high temperatures.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean occupies an elongated, S-shaped basin extending longitudinally between Europe and Africa to the east, and the Americas to the west.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] As one component of the interconnected World Ocean, it is connected in the north to the Arctic Ocean, to the Pacific Ocean in the southwest, the Indian Ocean in the southeast, and the Southern Ocean in the south.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other definitions describe the Atlantic as extending southward to Antarctica.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is divided in two parts, the northern and southern Atlantic, by the Equator.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oldest known mentions of an "Atlantic" sea come from Stesichorus around mid-sixth century BC (Sch.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] 211): *Atlantikôi pelágei* (Ancient Greek: Ἀτλαντικῷ πελάγει, 'the Atlantic sea', etym.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] 'Sea of Atlas') and in *The Histories* of Herodotus around 450 BC (Hdt.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] 1.202.4): *Atlantis thalassa* (Ancient Greek: Ἀτλαντὶς θάλασσα, 'Sea of Atlas' or 'the Atlantic sea'), where the name refers to "the sea beyond the pillars of Hercules" (the Strait of Gibraltar), beyond the Atlas Mountains in Morocco and off the West African coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In these uses, the name refers to Atlas, the Titan in Greek mythology, who supported the heavens and who later appeared as a frontispiece in medieval maps and atlases.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Early Greek sailors believed the Atlantic to be part of the Oceanus, the great sea or river that surrounds all land, mentioned in ancient Greek mythological literature such as the *Iliad* and *Odyssey*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This was in contrast to the enclosed seas well known to the Greeks, the Mediterranean and the Black Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The great ocean was believed to stretch around Africa, leading to the term "**Aethiopian Ocean**", derived from Ancient Ethiopia, applied to the southern Atlantic as late as the mid-19th century.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Age of Discovery, the Atlantic was also known to English cartographers as the **Great Western Ocean**.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The International Hydrographic Organization (IHO) defined the limits of the oceans and seas in 1953, but some of these definitions have been revised since then and some are not recognized by various authorities, institutions, and countries, such as the CIA World Factbook, for example.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Correspondingly, the extent and number of oceans and seas vary.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is bounded on the west by North and South America.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] It connects to the Arctic Ocean through the Labrador Sea, Denmark Strait, Greenland Sea, Norwegian Sea and Barents Sea with the northern divider passing through Iceland and Svalbard.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] To the east, the boundaries of the ocean proper are Europe and Africa: the Strait of Gibraltar (where it connects with the Mediterranean Sea – one of its marginal seas – and, in turn, the Black Sea, both of which also touch upon Asia).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the southeast, the Atlantic merges into the Indian Ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The 20° East meridian, running south from Cape Agulhas to Antarctica defines its border.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the 1953 definition it extends south to Antarctica, while in later maps it is bounded at the 60° parallel by the Southern Ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic has irregular coasts indented by numerous bays, gulfs and seas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] These include the Baltic Sea, Black Sea, Caribbean Sea, Davis Strait, Denmark Strait, part of the Drake Passage, Gulf of Mexico, Labrador Sea, Mediterranean Sea, North Sea, Norwegian Sea, almost all of the Scotia Sea, and other tributary water bodies.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Including these marginal seas the coast line of the Atlantic measures 111,866 km (69,510 mi) compared to 135,663 km (84,297 mi) for the Pacific.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Including its marginal seas, the Atlantic covers an area of 106,460,000 km2 (41,100,000 sq mi) or 23.5% of the global ocean and has a volume of 310,410,900 km3 (74,471,500 cu mi) or 23.3% of the total volume of the Earth's oceans.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The average depth is 3,646 m (11,962 ft) and the maximum depth, the Milwaukee Deep in the Puerto Rico Trench, is 8,376 m (27,480 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The bathymetry of the Atlantic is dominated by a submarine mountain range called the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (MAR).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] It runs from 87°N or 300 km (190 mi) south of the North Pole to the subantarctic Bouvet Island at 54°S.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Expeditions to explore the bathymertry of the Atlantic include the *Challenger* expedition and the German *Meteor* expedition; as of 2001, Columbia University's Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory and the United States Navy Hydrographic Office conduct research on the ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR divides the Atlantic longitudinally into two halves, in each of which a series of basins are delimited by secondary, transverse ridges.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR reaches above 2,000 m (6,600 ft) along most of its length, but is interrupted by larger transform faults at two places: the Romanche Trench near the Equator and the Gibbs fracture zone at 53°N.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR is a barrier for bottom water, but at these two transform faults deep water currents can pass from one side to the other.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR rises 2–3 km (1.2–1.9 mi) above the surrounding ocean floor and its rift valley is the divergent boundary between the North American and Eurasian plates in the North Atlantic and the South American and African plates in the South Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR produces basaltic volcanoes in Eyjafjallajökull, Iceland, and pillow lava on the ocean floor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The depth of water at the apex of the ridge is less than 2,700 m (1,500 fathoms; 8,900 ft) in most places, while the bottom of the ridge is three times as deep.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR is intersected by two perpendicular ridges: the Azores–Gibraltar transform fault, the boundary between the Nubian and Eurasian plates, intersects the MAR at the Azores triple junction, on either side of the Azores microplate, near the 40°N.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] A much vaguer, nameless boundary, between the North American and South American plates, intersects the MAR near or just north of the Fifteen-Twenty fracture zone, approximately at 16°N.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The remainder of the ridge was discovered in the 1920s by the German *Meteor* expedition using echo-sounding equipment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The exploration of the MAR in the 1950s led to the general acceptance of seafloor spreading and plate tectonics.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Most of the MAR runs under water but where it reaches the surfaces it has produced volcanic islands.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Continental shelves in the Atlantic are wide off Newfoundland, southernmost South America, and northeastern Europe.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the western Atlantic carbonate platforms dominate large areas, for example, the Blake Plateau and Bermuda Rise.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic is surrounded by passive margins except at a few locations where active margins form deep trenches: the Puerto Rico Trench (8,376 m or 27,480 ft maximum depth) in the western Atlantic and South Sandwich Trench (8,264 m or 27,113 ft) in the South Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] There are numerous submarine canyons off northeastern North America, western Europe, and northwestern Africa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Some of these canyons extend along the continental rises and farther into the abyssal plains as deep-sea channels.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1922, a historic moment in cartography and oceanography occurred.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The USS *Stewart* used a Navy Sonic Depth Finder to draw a continuous map across the bed of the Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This involved little guesswork because the idea of sonar is straightforward with pulses being sent from the vessel, which bounce off the ocean floor, then return to the vessel.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The deep ocean floor is thought to be fairly flat with occasional deeps, abyssal plains, trenches, seamounts, basins, plateaus, canyons, and some guyots.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Various shelves along the margins of the continents constitute about 11% of the bottom topography with few deep channels cut across the continental rise.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The mean depth between 60°N and 60°S is 3,730 m (12,240 ft), or close to the average for the global ocean, with a modal depth between 4,000 and 5,000 m (13,000 and 16,000 ft).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the South Atlantic the Walvis Ridge and Rio Grande Rise form barriers to ocean currents.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Laurentian Abyss is found off the eastern coast of Canada.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Surface water temperatures, which vary with latitude, current systems, and season and reflect the latitudinal distribution of solar energy, range from below −2 °C (28 °F) to over 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Maximum temperatures occur north of the equator, and minimum values are found in the polar regions.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the middle latitudes, the area of maximum temperature variations, values may vary by 7–8 °C (13–14 °F).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] From October to June the surface is usually covered with sea ice in the Labrador Sea, Denmark Strait, and Baltic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Coriolis effect circulates North Atlantic water in a clockwise direction, whereas South Atlantic water circulates counter-clockwise.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The south tides in the Atlantic Ocean are semi-diurnal; that is, two high tides occur every 24 lunar hours.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In latitudes above 40° North some east–west oscillation, known as the North Atlantic oscillation, occurs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] On average, the Atlantic is the saltiest major ocean; surface water salinity in the open ocean ranges from 33 to 37 parts per thousand (3.3–3.7%) by mass and varies with latitude and season.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Evaporation, precipitation, river inflow and sea ice melting influence surface salinity values.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Although the lowest salinity values are just north of the equator (because of heavy tropical rainfall), in general, the lowest values are in the high latitudes and along coasts where large rivers enter.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Maximum salinity values occur at about 25° north and south, in subtropical regions with low rainfall and high evaporation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The high surface salinity in the Atlantic, on which the Atlantic thermohaline circulation is dependent, is maintained by two processes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Agulhas Leakage/Rings brings salty Indian Ocean waters into the South Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] While the "Atmospheric Bridge" evaporates subtropical Atlantic waters and exports it to the Pacific.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean consists of four major, upper water masses with distinct temperature and salinity.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic subarctic upper water in the northernmost North Atlantic is the source for subarctic intermediate water and North Atlantic intermediate water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic central water can be divided into the eastern and western North Atlantic central water since the western part is strongly affected by the Gulf Stream and therefore the upper layer is closer to underlying fresher subpolar intermediate water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The eastern water is saltier because of its proximity to Mediterranean water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic central water flows into South Atlantic central water at 15°N.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] There are five intermediate waters: four low-salinity waters formed at subpolar latitudes and one high-salinity formed through evaporation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Arctic intermediate water flows from the north to become the source for North Atlantic deep water, south of the Greenland-Scotland sill.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] These two intermediate waters have different salinity in the western and eastern basins.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The wide range of salinities in the North Atlantic is caused by the asymmetry of the northern subtropical gyre and a large number of contributions from a wide range of sources: Labrador Sea, Norwegian-Greenland Sea, Mediterranean, and South Atlantic Intermediate Water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Along its path across Earth the composition of the NADW is affected by other water masses, especially Antarctic bottom water and Mediterranean overflow water.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The NADW is fed by a flow of warm shallow water into the northern North Atlantic which is responsible for the anomalous warm climate in Europe.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Changes in the formation of NADW have been linked to global climate changes in the past.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Since human-made substances were introduced into the environment, the path of the NADW can be traced throughout its course by measuring tritium and radiocarbon from nuclear weapon tests in the 1960s and CFCs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The clockwise warm-water North Atlantic Gyre occupies the northern Atlantic, and the counter-clockwise warm-water South Atlantic Gyre appears in the southern Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This system of currents transports warm water into the North Atlantic, without which temperatures in the North Atlantic and Europe would plunge dramatically.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] North of the North Atlantic Gyre, the cyclonic North Atlantic Subpolar Gyre plays a key role in climate variability.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] It is governed by ocean currents from marginal seas and regional topography, rather than being steered by wind, both in the deep ocean and at sea level.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The subpolar gyre forms an important part of the global thermohaline circulation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Its eastern portion includes eddying branches of the North Atlantic Current which transport warm, saline waters from the subtropics to the northeastern Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] There this water is cooled during winter and forms return currents that merge along the eastern continental slope of Greenland where they form an intense (40–50 Sv) current which flows around the continental margins of the Labrador Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] A third of this water becomes part of the deep portion of the North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The NADW, in turn, feeds the meridional overturning circulation (MOC), the northward heat transport of which is threatened by anthropogenic climate change.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Large variations in the subpolar gyre on a decade-century scale, associated with the North Atlantic oscillation, are especially pronounced in Labrador Sea Water, the upper layers of the MOC.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The South Atlantic is dominated by the anti-cyclonic southern subtropical gyre.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The South Atlantic Central Water originates in this gyre, while Antarctic Intermediate Water originates in the upper layers of the circumpolar region, near the Drake Passage and the Falkland Islands.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Both these currents receive some contribution from the Indian Ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] On the African east coast, the small cyclonic Angola Gyre lies embedded in the large subtropical gyre.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The southern subtropical gyre is partly masked by a wind-induced Ekman layer.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The residence time of the gyre is 4.4–8.5 years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic Deep Water flows southward below the thermocline of the subtropical gyre.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Sargasso Sea in the western North Atlantic can be defined as the area where two species of *Sargassum* (*S. fluitans* and *natans*) float, an area 4,000 km (2,500 mi) wide and encircled by the Gulf Stream, North Atlantic Drift, and North Equatorial Current.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This population of seaweed probably originated from Tertiary ancestors on the European shores of the former Tethys Ocean and has, if so, maintained itself by vegetative growth, floating in the ocean for millions of years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other species endemic to the Sargasso Sea include the sargassum fish, a predator with algae-like appendages which hovers motionless among the *Sargassum*.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Fossils of similar fishes have been found in fossil bays of the former Tethys Ocean, in what is now the Carpathian region, that were similar to the Sargasso Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] It is possible that the population in the Sargasso Sea migrated to the Atlantic as the Tethys closed at the end of the Miocene around 17 Ma.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The origin of the Sargasso fauna and flora remained enigmatic for centuries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The fossils found in the Carpathians in the mid-20th century often called the "quasi-Sargasso assemblage", finally showed that this assemblage originated in the Carpathian Basin from where it migrated over Sicily to the central Atlantic where it evolved into modern species of the Sargasso Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The location of the spawning ground for European eels remained unknown for decades.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the early 19th century it was discovered that the southern Sargasso Sea is the spawning ground for both the European and American eel and that the former migrate more than 5,000 km (3,100 mi) and the latter 2,000 km (1,200 mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Ocean currents such as the Gulf Stream transport eel larvae from the Sargasso Sea to foraging areas in North America, Europe, and northern Africa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Recent but disputed research suggests that eels possibly use Earth's magnetic field to navigate through the ocean both as larvae and as adults.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The climate is influenced by the temperatures of the surface waters and water currents as well as winds.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Because of the ocean's great capacity to store and release heat, maritime climates are more moderate and have less extreme seasonal variations than inland climates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Precipitation can be approximated from coastal weather data and air temperature from water temperatures.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oceans are the major source of atmospheric moisture that is obtained through evaporation.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Climatic zones vary with latitude; the warmest zones stretch across the Atlantic north of the equator.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The coldest zones are in high latitudes, with the coldest regions corresponding to the areas covered by sea ice.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Ocean currents influence the climate by transporting warm and cold waters to other regions.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The winds that are cooled or warmed when blowing over these currents influence adjacent land areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gulf Stream and its northern extension towards Europe, the North Atlantic Drift is thought to have at least some influence on climate.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] For example, the Gulf Stream helps moderate winter temperatures along the coastline of southeastern North America, keeping it warmer in winter along the coast than inland areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gulf Stream also keeps extreme temperatures from occurring on the Florida Peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the higher latitudes, the North Atlantic Drift, warms the atmosphere over the oceans, keeping the British Isles and northwestern Europe mild and cloudy, and not severely cold in winter, like other locations at the same high latitude.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The cold water currents contribute to heavy fog off the coast of eastern Canada (the Grand Banks of Newfoundland area) and Africa's northwestern coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In general, winds transport moisture and air over land areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Every winter, the Icelandic Low produces frequent storms.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Icebergs are common from early February to the end of July across the shipping lanes near the Grand Banks of Newfoundland.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The ice season is longer in the polar regions, but there is little shipping in those areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Hurricanes are a hazard in the western parts of the North Atlantic during the summer and autumn.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Due to a consistently strong wind shear and a weak Intertropical Convergence Zone, South Atlantic tropical cyclones are rare.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is underlain mostly by dense mafic oceanic crust made up of basalt and gabbro and overlain by fine clay, silt and siliceous ooze on the abyssal plain.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The continental margins and continental shelf mark lower density, but greater thickness felsic continental rock that is often much older than that of the seafloor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oldest oceanic crust in the Atlantic is up to 145 million years and is situated off the west coast of Africa and the east coast of North America, or on either side of the South Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In many places, the continental shelf and continental slope are covered in thick sedimentary layers.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] For instance, on the North American side of the ocean, large carbonate deposits formed in warm shallow waters such as Florida and the Bahamas, while coarse river outwash sands and silt are common in shallow shelf areas like the Georges Bank.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Coarse sand, boulders, and rocks were transported into some areas, such as off the coast of Nova Scotia or the Gulf of Maine during the Pleistocene ice ages.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The break-up of Pangaea began in the central Atlantic, between North America and Northwest Africa, where rift basins opened during the Late Triassic and Early Jurassic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This period also saw the first stages of the uplift of the Atlas Mountains.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The exact timing is controversial with estimates ranging from 200 to 170 Ma.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Theoliitic dikes, sills, and lava flows from the CAMP eruption at 200 Ma have been found in West Africa, eastern North America, and northern South America.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The extent of the volcanism has been estimated to 4.5×106 km2 (1.7×106 sq mi) of which 2.5×106 km2 (9.7×105 sq mi) covered what is now northern and central Brazil.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The formation of the Central American Isthmus closed the Central American Seaway at the end of the Pliocene 2.8 Ma ago.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The formation of the isthmus resulted in the migration and extinction of many land-living animals, known as the Great American Interchange, but the closure of the seaway resulted in a "Great American Schism" as it affected ocean currents, salinity, and temperatures in both the Atlantic and Pacific.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Marine organisms on both sides of the isthmus became isolated and either diverged or went extinct.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Geologically, the North Atlantic is the area delimited to the south by two conjugate margins, Newfoundland and Iberia, and to the north by the Arctic Eurasian Basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The opening of the North Atlantic closely followed the margins of its predecessor, the Iapetus Ocean, and spread from the central Atlantic in six stages: Iberia–Newfoundland, Porcupine–North America, Eurasia–Greenland, Eurasia–North America.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Active and inactive spreading systems in this area are marked by the interaction with the Iceland hotspot.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Seafloor spreading led to the extension of the crust and the formation of troughs and sedimentary basins.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Rockall Trough opened between 105 and 84 million years ago although the rift failed along with one leading into the Bay of Biscay.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Spreading began opening the Labrador Sea around 61 million years ago, continuing until 36 million years ago.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Geologists distinguish two magmatic phases.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] One from 62 to 58 million years ago predates the separation of Greenland from northern Europe while the second from 56 to 52 million years ago happened as the separation occurred.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Iceland began to form 62 million years ago due to a particularly concentrated mantle plume.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Large quantities of basalt erupted at this time period are found on Baffin Island, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, and Scotland, with ash falls in Western Europe acting as a stratigraphic marker.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The opening of the North Atlantic caused a significant uplift of continental crust along the coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] For instance, despite 7 km thick basalt, Gunnbjorn Field in East Greenland is the highest point on the island, elevated enough that it exposes older Mesozoic sedimentary rocks at its base, similar to old lava fields above sedimentary rocks in the uplifted Hebrides of western Scotland.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The North Atlantic Ocean contains about 810 seamounts, most of them situated along the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The OSPAR database (Convention for the Protection of the Marine Environment of the North-East Atlantic) mentions 104 seamounts: 74 within national exclusive economic zones.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Of these seamounts, 46 are located close to the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] West Gondwana (South America and Africa) broke up in the Early Cretaceous to form the South Atlantic.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The apparent fit between the coastlines of the two continents was noted on the first maps that included the South Atlantic and it was also the subject of the first computer-assisted plate tectonic reconstructions in 1965.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This magnificent fit, however, has since then proven problematic and later reconstructions have introduced various deformation zones along the shorelines to accommodate the northward-propagating break-up.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Intra-continental rifts and deformations have also been introduced to subdivide both continental plates into sub-plates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the southern segment the Early Cretaceous (133–130 Ma) intensive magmatism of the Paraná–Etendeka Large Igneous Province produced by the Tristan hotspot resulted in an estimated volume of 1.5×106 to 2.0×106 km3 (3.6×105 to 4.8×105 cu mi).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Dyke swarms in Brazil, Angola, eastern Paraguay, and Namibia, however, suggest the LIP originally covered a much larger area and also indicate failed rifts in all these areas.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Associated offshore basaltic flows reach as far south as the Falkland Islands and South Africa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Traces of magmatism in both offshore and onshore basins in the central and southern segments have been dated to 147–49 Ma with two peaks between 143 and 121 Ma and 90–60 Ma.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the Falkland segment rifting began with dextral movements between the Patagonia and Colorado sub-plates between the Early Jurassic (190 Ma) and the Early Cretaceous (126.7 Ma).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Around 150 Ma sea-floor spreading propagated northward into the southern segment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] No later than 130 Ma rifting had reached the Walvis Ridge–Rio Grande Rise.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the central segment, rifting started to break Africa in two by opening the Benue Trough around 118 Ma.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Rifting in the central segment, however, coincided with the Cretaceous Normal Superchron (also known as the Cretaceous quiet period), a 40 Ma period without magnetic reversals, which makes it difficult to date sea-floor spreading in this segment.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The equatorial segment is the last phase of the break-up, but, because it is located on the Equator, magnetic anomalies cannot be used for dating.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Various estimates date the propagation of seafloor spreading in this segment and consequent opening of the Equatorial Atlantic Gateway (EAG) to the period 120–96 Ma.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This final stage, nevertheless, coincided with or resulted in the end of continental extension in Africa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] About 50 Ma the opening of the Drake Passage resulted from a change in the motions and separation rate of the South American and Antarctic plates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] First, small ocean basins opened and a shallow gateway appeared during the Middle Eocene.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] 34–30 Ma a deeper seaway developed, followed by an Eocene–Oligocene climatic deterioration and the growth of the Antarctic ice sheet.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] An embryonic subduction margin is potentially developing west of Gibraltar.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gibraltar Arc in the western Mediterranean is migrating westward into the central Atlantic where it joins the converging African and Eurasian plates.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Together these three tectonic forces are slowly developing into a new subduction system in the eastern Atlantic Basin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Meanwhile, the Scotia Arc and Caribbean plate in the western Atlantic Basin are eastward-propagating subduction systems that might, together with the Gibraltar system, represent the beginning of the closure of the Atlantic Ocean and the final stage of the Atlantic Wilson cycle.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other theories propose that the Atlantic will continue to widen while the Pacific Ocean closes first.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This would create the future supercontinent Amasia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This theory states over the next 200 to 300 million years, dominant subduction in the Pacific will close the ocean while the Atlantic continues to get wider.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) studies indicate that 80,000–60,000 years ago a major demographic expansion within Africa, derived from a single, small population, coincided with the emergence of behavioral complexity and the rapid MIS 5–4 environmental changes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This group of people not only expanded over the whole of Africa, but also started to disperse out of Africa into Asia, Europe, and Australasia around 65,000 years ago and quickly replaced the archaic humans in these regions.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) 20,000 years ago humans had to abandon their initial settlements along the European North Atlantic coast and retreat to the Mediterranean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Following rapid climate changes at the end of the LGM this region was repopulated by Magdalenian culture.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other hunter-gatherers followed in waves interrupted by hazards such as the Laacher See volcanic eruption, the inundation of Doggerland (now the North Sea), and the formation of the Baltic Sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The European coasts of the North Atlantic were permanently populated about 9,000–8.5,000 years ago.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This human dispersal left abundant traces along the coasts of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] 50 kya-old, deeply stratified shell middens found in Ysterfontein on the western coast of South Africa are associated with the Middle Stone Age (MSA).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MSA population was small and dispersed and the rate of their reproduction and exploitation was less intense than those of later generations.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] While their middens resemble 12–11 kya-old Late Stone Age (LSA) middens found on every inhabited continent, the 50–45 kya-old Enkapune Ya Muto in Kenya probably represents the oldest traces of the first modern humans to disperse out of Africa.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The same development can be seen in Europe.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In La Riera Cave (23–13 kya) in Asturias, Spain, only some 26,600 molluscs were deposited over 10 kya.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In contrast, 8–7 kya-old shell middens in Portugal, Denmark, and Brazil generated thousands of tons of debris and artefacts.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Ertebølle middens in Denmark, for example, accumulated 2,000 m3 (71,000 cu ft) of shell deposits representing some 50 million molluscs over only a thousand years.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The earliest exploitation took place on the submerged shelves, now submerged and most settlements now excavated were then located several kilometers from these shelves.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The reduced quantities of shells in the lower levels can represent the few shells that were exported inland.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the LGM the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered most of northern North America while Beringia connected Siberia to Alaska.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1973, late American geoscientist Paul S.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Furthermore, colonisation models based on mtDNA, yDNA, and atDNA data respectively support neither the "blitzkrieg" nor the "three-wave" hypotheses but they also deliver mutually ambiguous results.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Contradictory data from archaeology and genetics will most likely deliver future hypotheses that will, eventually, confirm each other.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] A proposed route across the Pacific to South America could explain early South American finds and another hypothesis proposes a northern path, through the Canadian Arctic and down the North American Atlantic coast.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Early settlements across the Atlantic have been suggested by alternative theories, ranging from purely hypothetical to mostly disputed, including the Solutrean hypothesis and some of the Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact theories.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Norse settlement of the Faroe Islands and Iceland began during the 9th and 10th centuries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] A settlement on Greenland was established before 1000 CE, but contact with it was lost in 1409 and it was finally abandoned during the early Little Ice Age.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Iceland was initially settled 865–930 CE following a warm period when winter temperatures hovered around 2 °C (36 °F) which made farming favorable at high latitudes.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] This did not last, however, and temperatures quickly dropped; at 1080 CE summer temperatures had reached a maximum of 5 °C (41 °F).
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The *Landnámabók* (*Book of Settlement*) records disastrous famines during the first century of settlement – "men ate foxes and ravens" and "the old and helpless were killed and thrown over cliffs" – and by the early 1200s hay had to be abandoned for short-season crops such as barley.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492, sailing under the Spanish flag.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Six years later Vasco da Gama reached India under the Portuguese flag, by navigating south around the Cape of Good Hope, thus proving that the Atlantic and Indian Oceans are connected.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1500, in his voyage to India following Vasco da Gama, Pedro Álvares Cabral reached Brazil, taken by the currents of the South Atlantic Gyre.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Following these explorations, Spain and Portugal quickly conquered and colonized large territories in the New World and forced the Amerindian population into slavery in order to exploit the vast quantities of silver and gold they found.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Spain and Portugal monopolized this trade in order to keep other European nations out, but conflicting interests nevertheless led to a series of Spanish-Portuguese wars.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] A peace treaty mediated by the Pope divided the conquered territories into Spanish and Portuguese sectors while keeping other colonial powers away.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] England, France, and the Dutch Republic enviously watched the Spanish and Portuguese wealth grow and allied themselves with pirates such as Henry Mainwaring and Alexandre Exquemelin.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] They could explore the convoys leaving the Americas because prevailing winds and currents made the transport of heavy metals slow and predictable.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Between the 15th century and 1888, when Brazil became the last part of the Americas to end the slave trade, an estimated 9.5 million enslaved Africans were shipped into the New World, most of them destined for agricultural labor.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] The slave trade was officially abolished in the British Empire and the United States in 1808, and slavery itself was abolished in the British Empire in 1838 and in the United States in 1865 after the Civil War.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] From Columbus to the Industrial Revolution trans-Atlantic trade, including colonialism and slavery, became crucial for Western Europe.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] For European countries with direct access to the Atlantic (including Britain, France, the Netherlands, Portugal, and Spain) 1500–1800 was a period of sustained growth during which these countries grew richer than those in Eastern Europe and Asia.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Colonialism evolved as part of the trans-Atlantic trade, but this trade also strengthened the position of merchant groups at the expense of monarchs.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Growth was more rapid in non-absolutist countries, such as Britain and the Netherlands, and more limited in absolutist monarchies, such as Portugal, Spain, and France, where profit mostly or exclusively benefited the monarchy and its allies.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Trans-Atlantic trade also resulted in increasing urbanization: in European countries facing the Atlantic, urbanization grew from 8% in 1300, 10.1% in 1500, to 24.5% in 1850; in other European countries from 10% in 1300, 11.4% in 1500, to 17% in 1850.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] Likewise, GDP doubled in Atlantic countries but rose by only 30% in the rest of Europe.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p01] By the end of the 17th century, the volume of the Trans-Atlantic trade had surpassed that of the Mediterranean trade.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] The Atlantic has contributed significantly to the development and economy of surrounding countries.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] Besides major transatlantic transportation and communication routes, the Atlantic offers abundant petroleum deposits in the sedimentary rocks of the continental shelves.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] The Atlantic harbors petroleum and gas fields, fish, marine mammals (seals and whales), sand and gravel aggregates, placer deposits, polymetallic nodules, and precious stones.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] Gold deposits are a mile or two underwater on the ocean floor, however, the deposits are also encased in rock that must be mined through.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] Currently, there is no cost-effective way to mine or extract gold from the ocean to make a profit.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] Various international treaties attempt to reduce pollution caused by environmental threats such as oil spills, marine debris, and the incineration of toxic wastes at sea.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] The shelves of the Atlantic hosts one of the world's richest fishing resources.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] The most productive areas include the Grand Banks of Newfoundland, the Scotian Shelf, Georges Bank off Cape Cod, the Bahama Banks, the waters around Iceland, the Irish Sea, the Bay of Fundy, the Dogger Bank of the North Sea, and the Falkland Banks.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] The third group, "continuously increasing trend since 1950", is only found in the Indian Ocean and western Pacific.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] Northeast Atlantic is schematically limited to the 40°00' west longitude (except around Greenland), south to the 36°00' north latitude, and to the 68°30' east longitude, with both the west and east longitude limits reaching to the north pole.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northeast Atlantic total catches decreased between the mid-1970s and the 1990s and reached 8.7 million tons in 2013.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] reached a 2.4 million tons peak in 2004 but was down to 628,000 tons in 2013.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] Recovery plans for cod, sole, and plaice have reduced mortality in these species.
[src:atlantic-ocean/atlantic-ocean-p02] reached its lowest levels in the 1960s–1980s but is now recovered.
